WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Benjamin Franklin once said, quote, democracy is two wolves and a lamb voting on what they

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:13.880
[Amit Varma]: are going to have for lunch, stop quote.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:18.040
[Amit Varma]: That tells you from a lamb's point of view, that democracy is not enough.

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:20.900
[Amit Varma]: The wolves are going to vote to eat the lamb.

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:26.280
[Amit Varma]: Democracy by itself is meaningless unless you have a set of rules to protect every individual.

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:30.920
[Amit Varma]: The rules have to state that the wolves may not eat the lamb, no matter how lofty the

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:32.600
[Amit Varma]: stated purpose may be.

00:00:32.600 --> 00:00:36.440
[Amit Varma]: In modern times, we call these rules a constitution.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:40.920
[Amit Varma]: The constitution is a book of rules that protects the rights of lambs by limiting the behavior

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:41.920
[Amit Varma]: of wolves.

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:42.920
[Amit Varma]: That's right.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:47.960
[Amit Varma]: A constitution should ideally limit what a state can do to its citizens.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:50.160
[Amit Varma]: But this raises a difficult question.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.560
[Amit Varma]: What if a popular leader says that, hey, listen, I have the people of this nation with me.

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:56.720
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, I am legitimate.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.040
[Amit Varma]: This constitution is only legitimate as long as I say so.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:03.600
[Amit Varma]: If I don't agree with some part of it, I will change it.

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:05.040
[Amit Varma]: What happens to the lamb then?

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:08.200
[Amit Varma]: Is this attitude something we should be worried about in India?

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, 70 years ago, this was the exact position taken by Jawaharlal Nehru.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.440
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:23.440
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.680
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:30.160
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:33.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, we live in times when everyone looks at the world through binaries.

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:35.680
[Amit Varma]: If you're not with us, you're against us.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.720
[Amit Varma]: If you're not the purest of white, you're the blackest of black.

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:43.200
[Amit Varma]: This has especially happened since 2014, when Narendra Modi won elections.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:47.080
[Amit Varma]: For members of the tribe of Modi, history ended in 2014.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:50.400
[Amit Varma]: Nothing after that can be discussed and everything is Nehru's fault.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:54.240
[Amit Varma]: For people in the anti-Modi tribe, history began in 2014.

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:57.600
[Amit Varma]: We can only talk about the wrong that has happened since then.

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:00.600
[Amit Varma]: Before that, India was a golden age and our leaders were saints.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:06.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is obviously a ridiculous binary and it affects how we look at history.

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Consider Nehru, for example, who for one side is a saint and for the other side, a demon.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:13.080
[Amit Varma]: Nehru was a complex man.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:17.440
[Amit Varma]: He was a great leader during the freedom struggle and when he became prime minister of India,

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:20.160
[Amit Varma]: he got some things right and he got some things wrong.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:24.800
[Amit Varma]: You can ascribe some of his mistakes to the temper of the times and you can ascribe some

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:26.880
[Amit Varma]: of them to his own temperament.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Nehru contained multitudes.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.440
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, our constitution contains multitudes.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:36.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, people often speak of the constitution as if it is some sort of holy book, but the

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:38.720
[Amit Varma]: truth is it's not a book at all.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:44.280
[Amit Varma]: It was a book for just over a year between 1950 and 1951, after which, as one famous

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:49.120
[Amit Varma]: cartoon says, it ceased to be a book and became a periodical.

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:53.320
[Amit Varma]: Starting with Nehru, it became common that whenever a court called an action by a prime

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:57.920
[Amit Varma]: minister unconstitutional, the prime minister just went and changed the constitution.

00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:03.160
[Amit Varma]: The first amendment came in 1951 and in that, as well as through subsequent amendments like

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:08.520
[Amit Varma]: the third, the fourth, the seventh, the 17th, our rights were diluted as the constitution

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:10.900
[Amit Varma]: became less and less liberal.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:15.840
[Amit Varma]: No less than the father of the constitution, B. R. Ambedkar, said in 1954, at the time

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:20.640
[Amit Varma]: of the fourth amendment, that the constitution had been so degraded that he wanted to burn

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:21.640
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.480
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar, of course, was in the government at the time of the first amendment, which

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:28.400
[Amit Varma]: is such a fascinating period in India's history.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:32.320
[Amit Varma]: The government in power at the time, led by Nehru, realized that the constitution came

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:35.200
[Amit Varma]: in the way of much of what they wanted to accomplish.

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:37.240
[Amit Varma]: So they set about to amend it.

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:42.120
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a scholar, Tripur Dhaman Singh, who has written an excellent book called

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:48.100
[Amit Varma]: 16 Stormy Days, 16 Stormy Days lays out the details of the complex political landscape

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:54.480
[Amit Varma]: of those times, showing how so many of the leaders involved, including Nehru, were creatures

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:55.740
[Amit Varma]: of circumstance.

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:58.240
[Amit Varma]: You could even say they were responding to incentives.

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:03.040
[Amit Varma]: I wish every Indian, especially every Indian on Twitter would read this book, because it

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:07.840
[Amit Varma]: would give so much nuance to their understanding of Indian politics.

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:11.200
[Amit Varma]: One of my big learnings from the book was about our free speech laws.

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:16.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm a free speech absolutist, and I've always railed in column after column after column

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:22.160
[Amit Varma]: against section 124A of the Indian Penal Code, which is a sedition law, as well as 153A and

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:23.680
[Amit Varma]: 295A.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:27.240
[Amit Varma]: These are all colonial era laws, they should not exist today, right?

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:33.400
[Amit Varma]: Well, as Tripur Dhaman points out, these laws were deemed to be unconstitutional in 1950.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:39.440
[Amit Varma]: But the caveats to free speech added in the first amendment made them constitutional again.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:43.800
[Amit Varma]: That's some of the TIL moments in this superb book and in this episode.

