[Guest]: It's an absolute pleasure.

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:19.040
[Amit Varma]: Tripur Dhaman, before we get started talking about your fascinating book, which I enjoyed

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:23.400
[Amit Varma]: so much, and I wish many more people read and internalized, I'd love to know about your

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:24.400
[Amit Varma]: personal background.

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Like, how did you become a historian?

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:32.600
[Amit Varma]: What were your sort of intellectual influences, the historians that you looked up to?

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:37.120
[Amit Varma]: What drew you to history as a discipline?

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:42.080
[Guest]: So I actually have always had a kind of fascination for history and for politics.

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:47.600
[Guest]: And when I was going to university, I kind of really thought hard about, you know, which

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:48.600
[Guest]: line to take.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:50.920
[Guest]: And I ended up going with politics.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:57.480
[Guest]: But I found that I, while I did really enjoy the kind of, I studied politics and international

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:01.360
[Guest]: relations for my undergraduate degree, and I really enjoyed it.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:08.640
[Guest]: But I always felt that there was, that, I mean, history kind of always had a lot more

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:09.640
[Guest]: fascination.

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:14.480
[Guest]: I mean, it kind of interested me in a way that sort of political theory and international

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:16.280
[Guest]: relations theory didn't.

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:24.160
[Guest]: So then I ended up doing a master's in South Asian studies at Cambridge, where I was taken

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:27.640
[Guest]: on as a student by Christopher Bailey.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:31.200
[Guest]: And that was a very, that was my first real introduction to historical research.

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:33.720
[Guest]: It was kind of eye opening in many ways.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:39.080
[Guest]: It really kind of forced me to broaden the way I think, the way I kind of work.

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:44.600
[Guest]: And I think Bailey exercised like quite a great influence on me.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:48.680
[Guest]: And so that's how I ended up, and then because I did quite well, he was like, well, you should

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:49.680
[Guest]: think about a PhD.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.920
[Guest]: And I, you know, really liked him, I really liked what I did.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:57.880
[Guest]: And that was kind of how I, how I went into it.

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:04.000
[Guest]: And progressively, the more, I think the more I read and the more I came across, the more

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.260
[Guest]: I wanted to read and, you know, the more I wanted to get into the thick of sort of archival

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:11.600
[Guest]: action and research.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:16.920
[Guest]: And I think one thing really led to another and you, in the end, you know, that I've kind

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:20.680
[Guest]: of ended up doing this as an academic.

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:23.320
[Guest]: So, so far, so good, I'd say.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:27.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, while you got down to it, and you've written one book before this, and,

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:31.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, as you kind of approached that project, were you sort of just going with the flow

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:34.160
[Amit Varma]: and just picking up what interested you at the time?

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:39.300
[Amit Varma]: Or were there sort of themes that had always fascinated you, which you sort of took the

00:08:39.300 --> 00:08:41.120
[Amit Varma]: opportunity to explore?

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:47.420
[Guest]: So I actually started out with working on 18th and 19th century India.

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:54.040
[Guest]: Because that's what I had, you know, 10 years ago, that's what I thought was one of the

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:56.120
[Guest]: most fascinating periods of Indian history.

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:57.600
[Guest]: It still is.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:03.920
[Guest]: But it was, it was a kind of period of like, real flux.

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:08.400
[Guest]: And it's, it's the kind of period, say, someone like William Dalrymple writes about.

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:12.720
[Guest]: And some of the things that were kind of happening were just mind boggling.

00:09:12.720 --> 00:09:19.440
[Guest]: You had, you know, adventurers from Luxembourg setting up, you know, little kingdoms, you

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:24.440
[Guest]: had the kind of titular Mughal Empire still kind of soldiering on.

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:26.360
[Guest]: There was so much going on.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:33.480
[Guest]: And making sense of how things happened was constantly a sort of challenge.

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:38.480
[Guest]: Because I had never, when I did start with history, I'd never studied history academically

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:43.080
[Guest]: before, not for my undergraduate, not even for my, you know, final two years of school.

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:47.880
[Guest]: So I found the whole process of doing research really fascinating.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:52.320
[Guest]: And I think the 19th century was kind of a very, very interesting period to start with,

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: because it was one I was working with, I mean, possibly one of the greatest historians of

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.840
[Guest]: his generation.

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:06.160
[Guest]: And secondly, it was a kind of project which really needed you to, you know, dig into,

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:08.680
[Guest]: you know, quite old archival material.

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:13.000
[Guest]: It would take, you know, you would sit through 200-year-old documents.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.040
[Guest]: And I found the whole process really fascinating.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:21.640
[Guest]: And that period, because it's even now such a contested sort of time in Indian history,

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:26.560
[Guest]: we, it's, I mean, very politically charged to talk about, as you can see now, to talk

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:32.800
[Guest]: about, for example, the period which was the, you know, the end of the Mughal Empire and

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:36.640
[Guest]: the kind of rise of the British.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:43.800
[Guest]: And so I found, when I started out, I think I had a very, didn't have a very precise idea

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:45.960
[Guest]: of where the project would go.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:51.840
[Guest]: But as things developed, there were kind of certain themes which have really kind of stuck

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:53.280
[Guest]: with me since.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:59.520
[Guest]: And those include things like the idea of the law, the concept of sovereignty, the,

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:07.400
[Guest]: you know, how these sort of kind of small adventurers or small, like, kingdoms set up

00:11:07.400 --> 00:11:14.640
[Guest]: political entities within the sort of framework of the, you know, of the empire, really.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:17.200
[Guest]: And so I think those themes have kind of stuck with me.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:21.600
[Guest]: And some of them are kind of even reflected in this work on the Constitution, because

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:27.880
[Guest]: the idea of law and ideology is kind of laced through this work as well.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:29.400
[Amit Varma]: So a sort of a couple of questions.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:33.600
[Amit Varma]: One question is that, you know, most of us, when most of us non-historians, when we think

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:36.960
[Amit Varma]: of the telling of history, we think of it as, okay, you research a lot of facts, and

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:40.080
[Amit Varma]: you build a story around it, and you tell a story.

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:45.480
[Amit Varma]: But obviously, for a historian, you are sort of doing many different things.

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:50.480
[Amit Varma]: What is the process of doing history per se, as a historian, really like, you have to sort

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:56.680
[Amit Varma]: of set aside preconceptions and that you might have or that existing narratives about it.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:12:00.240
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the hindsight bias, where we already know what happened, but, you know,

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:03.960
[Amit Varma]: in the moment, it's never apparent what's going to happen.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:07.200
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of adjustments you have to make when you actually sit down to the

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:11.880
[Amit Varma]: practice of studying and writing history, especially as you say, since you, you know,

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:16.800
[Amit Varma]: took it up while, you know, in your post graduation, and you hadn't really studied the formal art

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:18.000
[Amit Varma]: of doing history before that?

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.360
[Guest]: I mean, I think it's quite hard to start from a kind of blank canvas.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:30.480
[Guest]: We all have certain biases, certain, I wouldn't say preconceptions, but certain ideas about

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:32.560
[Guest]: the world, about the past.

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:37.880
[Guest]: And I don't think you can start from a blank canvas, but you have to be willing to let

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:43.360
[Guest]: your own ideas be challenged, and be willing to kind of take them apart and put them back

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:44.360
[Guest]: together again.

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: And I think that's something that is really important, and that's something that I've

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.920
[Guest]: really learned through the last several years.

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:59.880
[Guest]: And I think one of the problems that I first had when I started my, I'd say my work as

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:08.520
[Guest]: a historian was my unfamiliarity with kind of the historiographical and methodological

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:14.240
[Guest]: tools that we use, because we do more than just tell a story.

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:19.840
[Guest]: And facts are always, I mean, facts are never really facts in the way that people often

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:20.840
[Guest]: understand them.

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:22.680
[Guest]: They have to be contextualized.

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:28.840
[Guest]: You have to interrogate your sources, because just because someone's saying something 200

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:33.160
[Guest]: years ago doesn't, you know, their word doesn't necessarily make it true.

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:35.680
[Guest]: So you have to be able to read them against the grain.

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:42.800
[Guest]: And you have to also think of how the world was at the period that you were writing about.

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:51.360
[Guest]: And that's where the kind of, a lot of the kind of theory that we forced to really, not

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:55.640
[Guest]: necessarily forced to, but you know, you have to come to terms with it, is sort of different

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:58.680
[Guest]: ways of conceptualizing the past.

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:06.120
[Guest]: And you have to be willing to, and that's, I feel that's where like most of the grunt

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:08.040
[Guest]: work really lies.

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:14.400
[Guest]: It's the sort of collection of facts and retelling of facts is the easy part, contextualizing

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:20.080
[Guest]: it and interpreting it in sort of in the light of, you know, the broader framework that you're

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:24.800
[Guest]: using to assess it or other ideas about the period that you're talking about.

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:30.120
[Guest]: That's where the real work lies, because you have to also take on board ideas that other

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:35.880
[Guest]: people have, which may be diametrically opposite to yours, and we can't simply ignore them

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:42.320
[Guest]: and say, well, I'm going to say this, which I guess you can in, you know, if you're writing

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:48.520
[Guest]: as an amateur or if you're, but for something to stand the kind of, stand the scrutiny of

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:54.360
[Guest]: your peers, it has to be willing to take on board a lot of ideas that you don't necessarily

00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:56.120
[Guest]: agree with.

00:14:56.120 --> 00:15:04.600
[Guest]: And I think that's one of the major, major differences between having a kind of, not

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:13.640
[Guest]: necessarily academic, but I'd say a professional historian versus a kind of raconteur of stories.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:17.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you mentioned that you spoke about the framework through which you approach

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.160
[Amit Varma]: history and you look at history.

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:23.960
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, as you said, none of us are blank slates going into looking at whatever

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:24.960
[Amit Varma]: we're looking at.

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:30.200
[Amit Varma]: So how much of this sort of framework was influenced by your studies of political science?

00:15:30.200 --> 00:15:33.600
[Amit Varma]: For example, you mentioned about how, you know, in your earlier book, you were interested

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:37.480
[Amit Varma]: in ideas of sovereignty and law and so on and so forth.

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:42.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, even in this book, there's a very, you know, a crisp, cogent, very lucid

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:49.160
[Amit Varma]: understanding of, you know, constitutionalism and liberalism and sort of the central fault

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:52.920
[Amit Varma]: lines of that period, which is, of course, the political imperatives of the Congress

00:15:52.920 --> 00:15:58.800
[Amit Varma]: party and Nehru versus a constitutional project that they had embarked upon, which is, you

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:03.920
[Amit Varma]: know, a very clear line and yet a frame that I haven't seen many other people who write

00:16:03.920 --> 00:16:06.520
[Amit Varma]: about that period use at all.

00:16:06.520 --> 00:16:10.760
[Amit Varma]: So how important was all of that political science training in defining sort of the way

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:11.760
[Amit Varma]: you look at history?

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:16.400
[Amit Varma]: And do you think that that's something that all historians sort of carry with them, that

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:17.880
[Amit Varma]: the frame also matters?

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:22.120
[Amit Varma]: It's not just, you know, how scrupulously you can, you know, get all the facts and tell

00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:25.160
[Amit Varma]: the story, but even the way you interpret it?

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:26.760
[Guest]: I mean, you're absolutely right.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:32.040
[Guest]: It does, the kind of the framework that you use and the kind of narrative that you build

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:35.980
[Guest]: are hugely important parts of the story you tell.

00:16:35.980 --> 00:16:45.440
[Guest]: And like my last book, because I felt this was, I mean, it's the kind of story that deserves

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:47.360
[Guest]: to be really widely read.

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:50.440
[Guest]: It's something that people are very unfamiliar with and something that affects everybody's

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:54.880
[Guest]: life quite intimately in ways that, you know, we don't often acknowledge.

00:16:54.880 --> 00:17:01.520
[Guest]: And for that reason, I tried to keep things as lucid, as crisp, as sort of easy to access

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:03.040
[Guest]: as I could.

00:17:03.040 --> 00:17:13.240
[Guest]: And that's because I was writing for an audience that may not necessarily be invested in history

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:19.760
[Guest]: in the same way as I would have written it if I was writing, you know, for Oxford University

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:22.440
[Guest]: Press.

00:17:22.440 --> 00:17:27.560
[Guest]: And I think that that kind of makes a huge difference.

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:34.320
[Guest]: As far as my sort of background in politics goes, it was, I think it gave me a good, it's

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:43.000
[Guest]: given me a good kind of basic idea of the kind of ideological elements that come into

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:52.800
[Guest]: being as well as the, I'd say, a sort of historical background of many of these ideas such as

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:55.440
[Guest]: liberalism or constitutionalism.

00:17:55.440 --> 00:18:02.720
[Guest]: And I think looking back, it's probably been quite helpful because I can perhaps talk about

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:09.120
[Guest]: both sides of the story with what I hope is like relative clarity.

00:18:09.120 --> 00:18:13.560
[Guest]: And I hope that that's something that comes across in the book as well.

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:16.520
[Amit Varma]: I was struck by the clarity of the writing and the fact that it's a book that can be

00:18:16.520 --> 00:18:21.000
[Amit Varma]: read by the lay reader and not someone who only reads history for that matter.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:26.520
[Amit Varma]: So were there any models in terms of historical writing that you looked at for this kind of

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:27.520
[Guest]: book?

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:29.360
[Guest]: There isn't really a specific model.

00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:34.800
[Guest]: I think it's just something that's come to me through reading a lot of historians.

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:40.840
[Guest]: And there are some books which really are very, very interesting, but then they're also

00:18:40.840 --> 00:18:45.880
[Guest]: written in a kind of way that makes them quite dull to read.

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:54.080
[Guest]: And I'd read them through because of the level of interest that I have in it, but someone

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:56.120
[Guest]: else might not.

00:18:56.120 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: And I think my thought always was that anyone with a slight interest in history or politics

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:06.120
[Guest]: should be able to pick this book up and be able to read it, no matter whether they're

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:12.440
[Guest]: like 16 or whether they're 60, and be able to make sense of it because it's not the easiest

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:14.120
[Guest]: subject to talk about.

00:19:14.120 --> 00:19:16.360
[Guest]: But on the other hand, it's hugely important.

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:21.160
[Guest]: And I think that's part and parcel of a historian's craft is to, especially if you're writing

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:28.120
[Guest]: about something that has such a huge bearing on the contemporary world, to make your material

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:30.760
[Guest]: accessible to a wide audience.

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:36.480
[Guest]: And I think one of the ideas, and this is like what I once watched, well, I watched

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:42.600
[Guest]: the film a long time ago, but I once read a review of the old Hindi film Dhundh, which

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:44.800
[Guest]: is from the 1970s.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:49.680
[Guest]: And the reviewer wrote, one of the reasons that he really loved the film was that he

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:54.840
[Guest]: was like, yeah, the action moves at the pace of a gunshot.

00:19:54.840 --> 00:19:58.840
[Guest]: And that's something that's always struck with me, is you shouldn't make things more

00:19:58.840 --> 00:20:05.520
[Guest]: complicated than they are, and you shouldn't unnecessarily pad out what you want to say.

00:20:05.520 --> 00:20:09.560
[Guest]: So if it can be said in a kind of way that keeps the narrative flowing quickly, and it

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:14.280
[Guest]: can be said in a way that is, you know, clear and accessible, then that's what you should

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:15.520
[Amit Varma]: go for.

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:18.920
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that struck me was, like you said, it's a hugely important book, and we'll

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:23.720
[Amit Varma]: come to that when we discuss the book, but it also struck me that the writing of it at

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:28.920
[Amit Varma]: this time is also surely something that you must have thought twice about, because, you

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:33.960
[Amit Varma]: know, doing history means you're embracing nuance, you know, as you have done in this

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:34.960
[Amit Varma]: book.

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:38.720
[Amit Varma]: But modern politics, especially in the last few years, is really the stripping away of

00:20:38.720 --> 00:20:41.880
[Amit Varma]: nuance and history has almost been weaponized.

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:46.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, we've created all these stark binaries through which we look at history,

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:50.760
[Amit Varma]: where for one side, you know, Nehru is all black, and for the other side, Nehru is all

00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:53.840
[Amit Varma]: white, and there's no other way of looking at it.

00:20:53.840 --> 00:20:58.320
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, you know, figures like Shama Prasad Mukherjee, and all of those, you know,

00:20:58.320 --> 00:21:01.680
[Amit Varma]: there are many people today who purport on the one hand to support the Congress, but

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.560
[Amit Varma]: on the other hand, they treat the Constitution almost as a holy book.

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:11.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, sometimes they will say in response to an argument, but that is unconstitutional

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:14.320
[Amit Varma]: as if that is automatically the end of the argument, and you don't need to say anything

00:21:14.320 --> 00:21:15.320
[Amit Varma]: about it.

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:19.080
[Amit Varma]: While the reality, of course, is that, you know, as that old cartoon goes, the Constitution

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:23.520
[Amit Varma]: is less of a book and more of a periodical, you know, Nehru, in fact, was in the habit

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:27.160
[Amit Varma]: of every time something he did was deemed unconstitutional.

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:31.800
[Amit Varma]: He simply amended the Constitution, not just in the First Amendment, as you write about,

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:36.420
[Amit Varma]: but the fourth, the seventh, the 17th, which went to Parliament just before he died, he

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:38.160
[Amit Varma]: sort of did this repeatedly.

00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:42.800
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you would have known when you began this book that this was sort of, you

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:47.320
[Amit Varma]: know, not fitting in these polarized times, it would just be, you know, it would not be

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:49.080
[Amit Varma]: an easy project to do.

00:21:49.080 --> 00:21:50.560
[Amit Varma]: What did you think about it in that sense?

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:56.040
[Amit Varma]: Like, did that increase the urgency of doing the book that, you know, something needs to

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:00.400
[Amit Varma]: counter the prevailing narratives, or is it something that made you think twice?

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:07.960
[Guest]: No, I think actually, that's one of the reasons why I really wrote it was that it sort of

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:13.120
[Guest]: inverts so many of these binaries that we've come to accept as a given.

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:19.020
[Guest]: And it really, it's, if somebody approaches it with an open mind, it kind of really scrambles

00:22:19.020 --> 00:22:26.640
[Guest]: the sort of easy, the kind of easy dichotomies that we draw.

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:34.200
[Guest]: And it is, yeah, it's a story that needs nuance, but equally, it's something that really sort

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:40.480
[Guest]: of has the potential to throw things a bit off kilter.

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:46.960
[Guest]: And yes, I knew when I wrote it that it, when I was writing it, that it has the potential

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:53.600
[Guest]: to be used as a kind of political tool in the current climate.

00:22:53.600 --> 00:22:59.360
[Guest]: But of course, I finished writing it before the kind of, you know, the protests over the

00:22:59.360 --> 00:23:05.080
[Guest]: CAA, etc. happened, which really brought the Constitution suddenly back into public debate.

00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:11.200
[Guest]: So it wasn't expressly written with the intent of being a kind of intervention in the debates

00:23:11.200 --> 00:23:12.760
[Guest]: of today.

00:23:12.760 --> 00:23:20.500
[Guest]: But I was well aware that it is something that impinges quite heavily on today's world.

00:23:20.500 --> 00:23:24.840
[Guest]: And the thing is, nobody comes out of it looking like you would expect.

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:31.620
[Guest]: So it has potential to be, I guess, used as a kind of intellectual weapon.

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:36.720
[Guest]: But I think that potential is open ended, so it can be used by either side to criticize

00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:38.160
[Guest]: the other.

00:23:38.160 --> 00:23:40.760
[Guest]: And I think that is something that I was aware of.

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's what makes it interesting.

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:44.040
[Amit Varma]: It's a fascinating book.

00:23:44.040 --> 00:23:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, for the human aspects of it, you know, you've kind of made all of

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:52.800
[Amit Varma]: these people, Nehru, Patel, Mukherjee, and so on, so much more three dimensional than

00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:54.560
[Amit Varma]: we otherwise knew of them.

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:58.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, just as you bring the lens of politics and political science, rather, in

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:03.480
[Amit Varma]: your telling of history, I kind of, you know, invoke economics in my podcast a lot.

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:09.120
[Amit Varma]: So as I was reading this book, it kind of, you know, confirmed my sense of how incentives

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:10.920
[Amit Varma]: shape actions and shape behavior.

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:15.480
[Amit Varma]: And I had a question for you on that, because one of the interesting things that you've

00:24:15.480 --> 00:24:21.200
[Amit Varma]: pointed out, and it's like a strand through the book, and it's endlessly fascinating is,

00:24:21.200 --> 00:24:25.180
[Amit Varma]: you know, and we'll discuss the book in detail, the context and everything that happened.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:29.680
[Amit Varma]: But one of the strands that really struck me was that at the time of the first amendment

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:34.400
[Amit Varma]: being carried out, you know, Raja ji and Ambedkar were both part of the establishment.

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:38.600
[Amit Varma]: And they played a part in actually getting many of these amendments through Raja ji,

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:44.460
[Amit Varma]: the sort of the anti free speech parts of it, and Ambedkar, all the rest of it.

00:24:44.460 --> 00:24:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And they were in government, and they were all for it.

00:24:46.600 --> 00:24:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And yet, after they are in government, as you pointed out, Ambedkar actually represented

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:55.560
[Amit Varma]: the zamindars against the very act that he had helped bring about.

00:24:55.560 --> 00:25:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, Raja ji goes on to form the Swatantra party and become a beacon of liberalism,

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:04.960
[Amit Varma]: while they're acting while in government is contrary to that.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:09.320
[Amit Varma]: And it sort of struck me about that old truism of Lord Acton that power corrupts.

00:25:09.320 --> 00:25:12.600
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that their behavior is actually entirely natural.

00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:16.660
[Amit Varma]: If you consider the incentives that if you're part of the executive, that arm of government,

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:20.600
[Amit Varma]: you will obviously be drawn to actions that strengthen the part of the government which

00:25:20.600 --> 00:25:21.900
[Amit Varma]: you are part of.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:23.920
[Amit Varma]: You might not think of it like that.

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:26.600
[Amit Varma]: But that's pretty much what you'll be drawn to.

00:25:26.600 --> 00:25:31.040
[Amit Varma]: So to me, it's not so much of a contradiction that when they were part of the government,

00:25:31.040 --> 00:25:33.740
[Amit Varma]: they behaved in a way that would stand in their arm of government.

00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And then once they are out of it, they can go back to talking about principles and you

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:43.920
[Amit Varma]: know, similarly, Nehru much earlier before he became Prime Minister warned of his own

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.800
[Amit Varma]: dictatorial tendencies.

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And yet when he became a Prime Minister, you know, he ignored the warnings of his past

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:53.960
[Amit Varma]: self, in a way, now, you've obviously, you know, studied that period and these people

00:25:53.960 --> 00:25:54.960
[Amit Varma]: much more than me.

00:25:54.960 --> 00:26:00.080
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of this that to what extent can they be and unconsciously, of course,

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:04.960
[Amit Varma]: not, you know, justifying it in these terms, but to what extent are they actually responding

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:08.240
[Amit Varma]: to incentives and can be read as creatures of their circumstances?

00:26:08.240 --> 00:26:12.280
[Guest]: They were definitely creatures of their circumstances.

00:26:12.280 --> 00:26:16.640
[Guest]: And that kind of comes through in the sort of reasons that they invoke.

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:22.840
[Guest]: And there is, I never quite point out, I mean, I never hint that they were, for example,

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:28.080
[Guest]: somehow inherently evil, or like somehow inherently, you know, their moral compass was corrupted.

00:26:28.080 --> 00:26:31.920
[Guest]: They were obviously responding to the situation as they saw it.

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:40.280
[Guest]: But the incentives part, how I put it is that they have, I think, part of it is to do with

00:26:40.280 --> 00:26:47.680
[Guest]: the fact that they were quite, as you know, Patel once, I pointed out at some point in

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:52.600
[Guest]: the book where Patel tells Nehru, you know, this is the result of idealistic exuberance.

00:26:52.600 --> 00:26:58.800
[Guest]: And I think the idealism had a major role to play somewhere, because they just passed

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:03.640
[Guest]: the Constitution, they had, you know, all of these grand ambitions, and they either

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:11.040
[Guest]: thought of themselves as kind of above these kind of despotic tendencies, or as people

00:27:11.040 --> 00:27:17.160
[Guest]: who would, you know, wield them with the idea of utmost benevolence.

00:27:17.160 --> 00:27:23.280
[Guest]: And that is, I feel, one major aspect of why they did what they did.

00:27:23.280 --> 00:27:28.800
[Guest]: Secondly, there was, of course, the incentive, and the incentive was driven also by the fact

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:34.200
[Guest]: that they were the only organized political force that there was.

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:42.240
[Guest]: So there was no real incentive to take on board the views of the opposition or the warnings,

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:47.240
[Guest]: you know, issued by, you know, figures like Mukherjee or Kripalani or people like that,

00:27:47.240 --> 00:27:53.640
[Guest]: because there was the idea that they would somehow, at some point, have to face the same

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:57.640
[Guest]: tools that they were crafting was just so far-fetched.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:28:07.800
[Guest]: And I think that probably made it easy enough to contemplate these measures that I think

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:13.880
[Guest]: they probably would not have if there had been any real political organization with

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:17.680
[Guest]: the standing to challenge the Congress.

00:28:17.680 --> 00:28:21.360
[Guest]: And I think that was one major incentive.

00:28:21.360 --> 00:28:26.320
[Guest]: I think the other, again, and this is, I think, quite common to most democracies, is that

00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:35.280
[Guest]: the incentive, if possible, to take shortcuts to gain political benefit is always there.

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:38.440
[Guest]: And a lot of these people quite clearly succumb to it.

00:28:38.440 --> 00:28:42.240
[Amit Varma]: There's a fascinating passage from your book, which I'll read out, which is, in fact, about

00:28:42.240 --> 00:28:46.240
[Amit Varma]: the Congress, where you write, from its earliest days, the Congress Party had claimed to speak

00:28:46.240 --> 00:28:49.320
[Amit Varma]: for the entirety of the nation and to represent all Indians.

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:53.320
[Amit Varma]: The party was as committed to denying every other group or party a seat at the political

00:28:53.320 --> 00:28:56.880
[Amit Varma]: high table as it was to gaining control of the levers of power.

00:28:56.880 --> 00:29:01.080
[Amit Varma]: As a self-declared representative of the nation, the Congress laid claim to possession of the

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:03.440
[Amit Varma]: colonial state and all its territory.

00:29:03.440 --> 00:29:08.120
[Amit Varma]: With the advent of democracy and the inauguration of the Constitution, this position, incompatible

00:29:08.120 --> 00:29:12.960
[Amit Varma]: with any idea of constitutional democracy, was strained to breaking point when its collectivist

00:29:12.960 --> 00:29:17.640
[Amit Varma]: mirrorings and its intolerance of opposing ideologies clashed with an expansively liberal

00:29:17.640 --> 00:29:18.680
[Amit Varma]: Constitution.

00:29:18.680 --> 00:29:22.680
[Amit Varma]: The Congress Party, instead of defending the normative foundations of democracy and the

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:29.240
[Amit Varma]: fundamental rights enshrined in the Constitution, instinctively turned on its own creation."

00:29:29.240 --> 00:29:33.960
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of, you know, in your book, what you've done an excellent job is of laying

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:40.280
[Amit Varma]: out the context of that immediate period between, you know, 26 Jan 1950, when the Constitution

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:45.600
[Amit Varma]: comes into being and, and then the First Amendment 14 months later, but give me a broader sense

00:29:45.600 --> 00:29:50.960
[Amit Varma]: of the context of these times as we, you know, come into this that what is a Congress's approach

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:57.520
[Amit Varma]: and my sense in us, in a way was that, you know, people like Nehru and Patel and whatever,

00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:02.880
[Amit Varma]: when they spoke so highly of the fundamental rights and all of that earlier, were in a

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:06.080
[Amit Varma]: sense doing what we would today call virtue signaling.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:12.040
[Amit Varma]: But when they realized that the, that it would impact their ability to do all the things

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:16.640
[Amit Varma]: that they wanted to do, which the Congress was predicated upon, because the whole Congress's

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:22.000
[Amit Varma]: platform was social change and a certain kind of progressive progressivism, which then those

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.520
[Amit Varma]: fundamental rights got in the way of.

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:28.120
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, how was all of that sort of playing out?

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:34.560
[Amit Varma]: Was this clash between fundamental rights and politics kind of inevitable in the way

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:39.440
[Amit Varma]: the last few years shaped up or, you know, was it sort of contingent upon the circumstance

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:41.920
[Amit Varma]: of Nehru being the person who happened to be the Prime Minister?

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:44.720
[Guest]: What is your sense of that?

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:50.440
[Guest]: A quick word about that quote, though, so that's a whole school of Indian history would

00:30:50.440 --> 00:30:52.400
[Guest]: kind of subscribe to that view.

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:55.960
[Guest]: And I think I referenced that to Sunil Khillani.

00:30:55.960 --> 00:30:59.880
[Guest]: But of course, there are also others like Barry Anderson, etc.

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:07.080
[Guest]: And it's so partition, for example, was something that was framed in Congress circles as a price

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:13.200
[Guest]: that they had to pay to have a centralized state under their own control.

00:31:13.200 --> 00:31:21.080
[Guest]: And that kind of reflects, again, I said, I think it kind of testifies to the idea that

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:26.880
[Guest]: I think that the Congress was quite committed to a centralized state under its own control.

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:32.640
[Guest]: And I mean, one of the sticking points throughout the 1930s and 1940s in Indian politics is

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:38.520
[Guest]: the Congress demand to be taken for, you know, the Congress demand for the British to consider

00:31:38.520 --> 00:31:42.400
[Guest]: it the sole representative of the nation.

00:31:42.400 --> 00:31:46.440
[Guest]: And ultimately, that's what becomes a stumbling block.

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:50.240
[Guest]: It becomes a stumbling block in the 40s with the rise of the Muslim League because it becomes

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:51.720
[Guest]: a position that's completely untenable.

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:55.260
[Guest]: You know, once the Muslim League wins the majority of Muslim seats, it becomes quite

00:31:55.260 --> 00:32:00.880
[Guest]: apparent that the Congress doesn't represent the entirety of the nation because they lose

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:03.840
[Guest]: quite badly in the Muslim seats.

00:32:03.840 --> 00:32:10.720
[Guest]: And that kind of idea still, but the idea doesn't really die because the thing is, it's

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:16.080
[Guest]: thought that that problem has been overcome, or at least sidelined with partition.

00:32:16.080 --> 00:32:23.040
[Guest]: And so once the exercise to, you know, write the Constitution, etc., begins, you have token

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:25.160
[Guest]: representation of other groups.

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:29.680
[Guest]: And I think it's done with the idea that, you know, you give the impression that it's

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:32.000
[Guest]: a very representative assembly.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:38.160
[Guest]: But as people never tire of pointing out, even during the Constituent Assembly debates,

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:42.960
[Guest]: it's essentially a one-party body in a one-party country.

00:32:42.960 --> 00:32:44.880
[Guest]: There is no other party.

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:48.920
[Guest]: And the party that dominates the Constituent Assembly also holds the levers of executive

00:32:48.920 --> 00:32:50.560
[Guest]: power.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:59.600
[Guest]: And once the Constitution comes into force, and everyone knows that an election is going

00:32:59.600 --> 00:33:05.680
[Guest]: to be held, it also creates a kind of incentive for people who are already, you know, in the

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:13.280
[Guest]: Constituent Assembly, and to kind of toe the orders that come from Nehru and Patel, because

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:16.240
[Guest]: a lot of them want to be re-elected.

00:33:16.240 --> 00:33:19.800
[Guest]: And the only way that they will get their nominations is if they keep the party bosses

00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:21.800
[Guest]: content.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:30.240
[Guest]: And so that's, again, contemporary sort of articles in the press speak about this openly.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:37.840
[Guest]: And then, of course, you also have the kind of decline of Sardar Patel, because he's,

00:33:37.840 --> 00:33:44.080
[Guest]: by the mid-1950s, he's actually bedridden for most of the time.

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:47.680
[Guest]: And he passes away in 1950.

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:52.880
[Guest]: And by then, Nehru is already more or less ascendant.

00:33:52.880 --> 00:33:57.800
[Guest]: I talk about it at some point in the book with the Nasik Congress, where in Patel's

00:33:57.800 --> 00:34:02.120
[Guest]: absence, you know, Nehru kind of has his own way.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:06.840
[Guest]: And eventually, after Patel's death, really, you have a system where Nehru is such a political

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:12.280
[Guest]: colossus that there is no one really in the cabinet who can, you know, stand up to him

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:18.760
[Guest]: or put forward a strong alternative position.

00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:26.680
[Guest]: Nehru's biographer Sarvapalli Gopal, who is actually very sympathetic to Nehru, you know,

00:34:26.680 --> 00:34:31.000
[Guest]: calls it a sort of collection of mouldering mediocrities.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:39.880
[Guest]: And so the context is that the political capital that Nehru brings to bear, much like today,

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:45.480
[Guest]: ensures that he is capable of getting his own way.

00:34:45.480 --> 00:34:51.760
[Guest]: And I think I make a reasonably strong case in the book for arguing that much of it is

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:57.960
[Guest]: driven by Nehru's own personal investment in these policies, rather than any sort of

00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:03.720
[Guest]: great pressure from the states, because he resists the pressure for things that he kind

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:05.920
[Guest]: of feels very strongly about.

00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:13.440
[Guest]: And on the other side, equally, you have figures like S. P. Mukherjee or H. N. Kundzor, or

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:16.560
[Guest]: even Kriplani, who then resigns from the Congress.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:22.040
[Guest]: They're very articulate, they're very good at, you know, the sort of ins and outs of

00:35:22.040 --> 00:35:23.480
[Guest]: parliamentary debate.

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:29.720
[Guest]: But unfortunately, no one has the kind of political organisation or the public standing

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:32.600
[Guest]: to mount a significant challenge.

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:39.560
[Guest]: And I think that's a kind of interesting thing to note, because it has so many contemporary

00:35:39.560 --> 00:35:42.800
[Guest]: echoes the way like we sort of conceptualise today.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:48.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, those contemporary echoes are, you know, sort of echoed as it were, throughout

00:35:48.480 --> 00:35:53.800
[Amit Varma]: my reading of the book, when, you know, because in our modern times as well, we seem to have

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:58.680
[Amit Varma]: a single party which is utterly dominant, as it was then, we have a larger than life

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:02.200
[Amit Varma]: figure in charge of that party.

00:36:02.200 --> 00:36:06.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, you just repeated a quote about the quality of Nehru's cabinet and a similar

00:36:06.040 --> 00:36:12.640
[Amit Varma]: thing could possibly be said about this one about, you know, how eminences like Arun Shourie

00:36:12.640 --> 00:36:16.400
[Amit Varma]: for example, were just sidelined in 2014.

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:19.720
[Amit Varma]: And you've got a much weaker cabinet than you could have.

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:26.560
[Amit Varma]: And equally, you have worries about the constitution about how it's been degraded and sort of made

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:31.040
[Amit Varma]: meaningless and how that particular arm of the state is being strengthened as compared

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:32.040
[Amit Varma]: to the others.

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:36.520
[Amit Varma]: Though those, you know, one could argue today that hey, the constitutions was already degraded

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:40.600
[Amit Varma]: that you talk of the, you know, I'm struck by something Kapil Komeredi said on Twitter,

00:36:40.600 --> 00:36:44.720
[Amit Varma]: where somebody was complaining about the murder of democracy when these recent farm bills

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:47.960
[Amit Varma]: were passed the way they were, which was a murder of democracy.

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:52.920
[Amit Varma]: But as Kapil pointed out, it was not just murder, it was also mimicry, because it's

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:54.360
[Amit Varma]: all happened before.

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:57.280
[Amit Varma]: And your book is very instructive in that regard.

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:02.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I used to often joke about how, you know, despite blaming Nehru for everything,

00:37:02.520 --> 00:37:05.720
[Amit Varma]: Modi is actually, you know, a mimic in many ways.

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and what I mainly meant was the whole central planning top down approach of the

00:37:10.960 --> 00:37:12.160
[Amit Varma]: economy.

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:18.360
[Amit Varma]: But even with the approach towards power, the approach to the constitution, it's extremely

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:19.360
[Amit Varma]: similar.

00:37:19.360 --> 00:37:24.600
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about what Nehru's imperatives and his incentives at the time

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:29.920
[Amit Varma]: were because he came in like 1950 is when the constitution is there, he is aware that

00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:34.080
[Amit Varma]: he is part of a government which hasn't yet got a popular mandate.

00:37:34.080 --> 00:37:38.280
[Amit Varma]: It's a transitionary government in that sense, he needs a popular mandate.

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:42.680
[Amit Varma]: Part of that mandate rests on fulfilling the promises he has made.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:48.280
[Amit Varma]: Those promises include the zamindari reforms and, you know, reservations and so on and

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:51.640
[Amit Varma]: so forth, the whole social, progressive element of it.

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly he finds that this constitution is in the way, you know, what the hell is

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:56.440
[Amit Varma]: going on?

00:37:56.440 --> 00:38:01.720
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about sort of, you know, what are his imperatives and how is he responding

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:02.720
[Guest]: to them?

00:38:02.720 --> 00:38:04.160
[Guest]: I think there are several actually.

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:13.560
[Guest]: So one of course is the fact that Nehru is, especially with zamindari abolition, that's

00:38:13.560 --> 00:38:18.000
[Guest]: a policy that Nehru is personally invested in and personally identified with.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:24.280
[Guest]: So the Congress Party runs a tremendous sort of public contact program really for zamindari

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:26.560
[Guest]: abolition.

00:38:26.560 --> 00:38:32.240
[Guest]: I think in UP alone there were like 35,000 public meetings.

00:38:32.240 --> 00:38:35.880
[Guest]: Probably Bihar had a similar number.

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:42.880
[Guest]: And so there's a lot of political capital that's being invested in this and, you know,

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:48.040
[Guest]: from the top to the bottom, from, you know, small-time leaders like district presidents

00:38:48.040 --> 00:38:53.040
[Guest]: to more senior figures such as, well, Nehru himself, but also figures like Charan Singh

00:38:53.040 --> 00:39:02.400
[Guest]: and C.B. Gupta, et cetera, who are very, very both vocal and kind of committed to a particular

00:39:02.400 --> 00:39:06.720
[Guest]: form of zamindari abolition and land reform.

00:39:06.720 --> 00:39:15.880
[Guest]: And of course, the Congress having acquired the levers of power is also a bit, I think

00:39:15.880 --> 00:39:22.720
[Guest]: the easiest way to describe it would be suffering from a slight hangover of the Raj because

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:32.360
[Guest]: it's hard to convince the public that having gotten rid of one set of rulers, the other

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:37.760
[Guest]: set of rulers do not have similar powers or are constrained by notions of constitutionalism

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:38.760
[Guest]: or legality.

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:47.040
[Guest]: So when the kind of first judgment, which is the staying of the Bihar Act, happens,

00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:52.840
[Guest]: it comes as a huge shock, not only because it kind of takes a sort of sledgehammer to

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:57.920
[Guest]: their political capital because it shows everyone that their word is not infallible, but also

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:01.660
[Guest]: because it's something that has been discussed over and over again within the Constituent

00:40:01.660 --> 00:40:03.080
[Guest]: Assembly.

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:07.520
[Guest]: And it was something, the right to property is something that had been debated extensively

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:14.200
[Guest]: in past as a form of compromise between those who were kind of votaries of a strong right

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:19.440
[Guest]: to private property and those who felt that it would come in the way of zamindari and

00:40:19.440 --> 00:40:20.720
[Guest]: land reform.

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:24.720
[Guest]: So this was something that had not been really considered possible.

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:29.520
[Guest]: Zamindari abolition had been considered a done deal and plenty of Congress figures are

00:40:29.520 --> 00:40:36.720
[Guest]: on record saying this is going to happen regardless of anything else, such as constitution or

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:41.040
[Guest]: no constitution, this zamindari abolition will come into place.

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:47.360
[Guest]: So once they realize that it can't, it kind of leads to a sort of real shockwave within

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:57.920
[Guest]: the Congress party and many suspect that with the money and the sort of local power that

00:40:57.920 --> 00:41:07.120
[Guest]: many of the zamindars have and can bring to bear, that the forthcoming election is something

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:12.520
[Guest]: to be really thought about because from the other side, and there are zamindari parties

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:17.640
[Guest]: which are in the fray and many of them are quite confident about being able to take on

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:18.720
[Guest]: the Congress.

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:25.720
[Guest]: So that's another thing that Nehru is acutely conscious of, that going back to the people

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:33.240
[Guest]: without fulfilling what he has personally promised would amount to a kind of betrayal.

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:37.360
[Guest]: And he says this in several letters to his chief ministers and to his colleagues that

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:41.680
[Guest]: it's something that he doesn't want to countenance.

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:48.600
[Guest]: Equally it's also something that state chief ministers do not want to countenance and Bihar

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:53.000
[Guest]: definitely doesn't want to countenance that and they become like the first sort of people

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:56.560
[Guest]: to demand a constitutional amendment to pass their law.

00:41:56.560 --> 00:42:03.220
[Guest]: There's of course a kind of longer story connected to that law, which is that Bihar law is a

00:42:03.220 --> 00:42:10.480
[Guest]: the only one that is found to be unconstitutional, unlike similar laws in UP and later in Maharashtra.

00:42:10.480 --> 00:42:16.560
[Guest]: The Bihar law is basically held to be unconstitutional on a technicality, not because it violates

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:20.360
[Guest]: the right to property but because it violates the right to equality.

00:42:20.360 --> 00:42:28.480
[Guest]: And so no one honestly believes that zamindari abolition is under such serious threat that

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:30.240
[Unknown]: a constitutional amendment is needed.

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:36.400
[Guest]: I mean no lesser person than the president of the republic, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, writes

00:42:36.400 --> 00:42:42.240
[Guest]: to Nehru to tell him that no such eventuality seems to have arisen.

00:42:42.240 --> 00:42:50.840
[Guest]: But I think it's again just the temptation to take a shortcut, to have your own way because

00:42:50.840 --> 00:42:52.960
[Guest]: it's politically expedient.

00:42:52.960 --> 00:43:01.760
[Guest]: It sort of trumps, I feel it trumps the commitment to the kind of ideals that they publicly professed.

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:02.760 --> 00:43:05.720
[Amit Varma]: And this was, of course, as you point out in your book, there are three prominent pain

00:43:05.720 --> 00:43:10.000
[Amit Varma]: points in which the constitution got in the way of what Nehru's government wanted to do

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:11.520
[Amit Varma]: and this was one of them.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:15.160
[Amit Varma]: Just to sort of get into the weeds and summarize briefly and you can tell me if I'm summarizing

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:16.160
[Amit Varma]: it correctly.

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:19.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, it was of course challenged on the grounds of both the right to property and

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:23.720
[Amit Varma]: the right to equality but the high court when striking it down in Bihar invoked the right

00:43:23.720 --> 00:43:30.880
[Amit Varma]: to equality per se because, you know, they were giving unequal compensation to the zamindars

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:35.840
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that the small zamindars were getting up to 20 times their annual revenues

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:39.240
[Amit Varma]: while others were getting eight times and some of the big biggest ones were getting

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:43.680
[Amit Varma]: three times or something like that and you know which they felt infringed the right to

00:43:43.680 --> 00:43:44.680
[Amit Varma]: equality.

00:43:44.680 --> 00:43:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Is that correct?

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:46.680
[Amit Varma]: These are the grounds.

00:43:46.680 --> 00:43:47.680
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:48.680
[Amit Varma]: You're right.

00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:49.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:50.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:54.160
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you've quoted a bunch of letters that Nehru has written, you know, on October

00:43:54.160 --> 00:43:59.840
[Amit Varma]: 18, 1950, he wrote to Shri Krishna Sinha, who was a CM of Bihar, when Nehru says, quote,

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:03.840
[Amit Varma]: I am as concerned as you are with these squibblings of lawyers coming in the way of our social

00:44:03.840 --> 00:44:04.840
[Amit Varma]: progress.

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:09.360
[Amit Varma]: I entirely agree with you that we shall have to consider seriously an amendment of the

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:10.360
[Amit Varma]: constitution.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.800
[Amit Varma]: I am consulting the law ministry in regard to it.

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:13.800
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:17.320
[Amit Varma]: And then again, you quote him in a letter to all his CMs on December 18th, where he

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:22.640
[Amit Varma]: says, quote, recent judgments of some high courts have made us think about our constitution.

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Is it adequate in its present form to meet the situation we have to face?

00:44:26.640 --> 00:44:31.120
[Amit Varma]: We must accept fully the judgment of our superior courts, but if they find that there is a lacuna

00:44:31.120 --> 00:44:34.840
[Amit Varma]: in the constitution, then we shall have to remedy that.

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:41.280
[Amit Varma]: It sort of reminds me of, I think the quip, I forget if it's by Brecht or whoever, that,

00:44:41.280 --> 00:44:44.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, if the people don't like the government, then the government shall have to elect the

00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:49.100
[Amit Varma]: new people or something of that sort, where Nehru's perspective is, does the constitution

00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:52.560
[Amit Varma]: fit what we want to do rather than the other way around?

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:57.200
[Amit Varma]: And like you pointed out, you know, everyone was saying that nowhere have the courts actually

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:02.120
[Amit Varma]: said that zamindari reforms are an issue or land redistribution is an issue.

00:45:02.120 --> 00:45:06.480
[Amit Varma]: It's very easy to be within the constitution and just revert the law a little bit to take

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:09.160
[Amit Varma]: care of these, but Nehru doesn't care to do that.

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:10.440
[Amit Varma]: So this is one of the fault lines.

00:45:10.440 --> 00:45:15.840
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about the sort of the other two fault lines and, you know, the key cases in sort

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:17.780
[Guest]: of those regards.

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:23.880
[Guest]: So the other two fault lines, one, of course, is over reservations, community-based reservations.

00:45:23.880 --> 00:45:29.800
[Guest]: And the other, which is the fault line, which the book begins with is over, and I think

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:35.960
[Guest]: something that's possibly the most relevant to the contemporary period is the question

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:44.600
[Guest]: of the right to freedom of speech, because we start with, at least I start the book with

00:45:44.600 --> 00:45:54.200
[Guest]: this, the case of the communist detainees in Salem who, I mean, there's a scuffle in

00:45:54.200 --> 00:46:01.040
[Guest]: Salem prison, and then finally the sort of enraged policemen lock these prisoners into

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:05.920
[Guest]: a hall and then open fire at them at point blank range.

00:46:05.920 --> 00:46:10.040
[Guest]: And I think some 200 end up getting shot.

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:17.640
[Guest]: And there are, I don't remember off the back of my head, but if I can.

00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:23.200
[Amit Varma]: I think you've pointed out how it kind of all begins where these detainees in Bombay,

00:46:23.200 --> 00:46:27.580
[Amit Varma]: they realize after, you know, 26 Jan, the constitution comes into place and these guys

00:46:27.580 --> 00:46:33.080
[Amit Varma]: realize that, according to article 22, there cannot be indefinite detention.

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:36.920
[Guest]: Indefinite detention without access to an advisory board.

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:38.600
[Guest]: And no such advisory boards existed.

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:43.240
[Guest]: So obviously the Bombay High Court doesn't buy the government's contention that the constitution

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:47.840
[Guest]: doesn't have retrospective effect or that law predates the constitution.

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:49.840
[Guest]: And they're let loose.

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:54.120
[Guest]: And of course, that's the kind of one of the first cases that brings, you know, fundamental

00:46:54.120 --> 00:46:55.840
[Guest]: rights into play.

00:46:55.840 --> 00:47:02.560
[Guest]: But then there's a kind of bigger question, which comes up after the shootings of the

00:47:02.560 --> 00:47:09.180
[Guest]: detainees in Salem in cold blood, because there is a kind of, there's a left-leaning

00:47:09.180 --> 00:47:17.000
[Guest]: magazine called Crossroads run by the young Romesh Thapar, who is coincidentally the brother

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.600
[Guest]: of the famous historian Romila Thapar.

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:28.880
[Guest]: But so Romesh Thapar's magazine, you know, eviscerates Nehru and the Congress and it

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:34.080
[Guest]: ends up getting banned in the Madras province.

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:37.440
[Guest]: And Thapar, of course, is not one to take it lying down.

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:42.600
[Guest]: He launches a collection, his readers sort of contribute to the effort and eventually

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:54.240
[Guest]: a petition is filed in the Supreme Court, arguing that the ban is unconstitutional.

00:47:54.240 --> 00:48:03.840
[Guest]: And this is, it's mirrored on the other side in Delhi, where a precensorship order is served

00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:09.600
[Guest]: against the organizer, which is the weekly news magazine of the RSS.

00:48:09.600 --> 00:48:14.280
[Guest]: And essentially the reason the government is upset with them is that they have been

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:22.320
[Guest]: criticizing the Nehru government's policies towards Pakistan in the context of what's

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:24.320
[Guest]: been happening in Bengal.

00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:31.800
[Guest]: Bengal had been seeing a lot of communal violence, triggered mainly by a sort of state-sponsored,

00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:36.920
[Guest]: I mean, I wouldn't necessarily call it a kind of genocide, but sort of state-sponsored communal

00:48:36.920 --> 00:48:41.120
[Guest]: attrition really in East Pakistan, which had led to a lot of refugees crossing over and

00:48:41.120 --> 00:48:45.360
[Guest]: obviously retaliatory violence in West Bengal.

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:54.480
[Guest]: So Nehru had been trying to essentially work out a kind of agreement with Liaqat Ali Khan

00:48:54.480 --> 00:49:00.280
[Guest]: on how they would stem the tide of the refugees.

00:49:00.280 --> 00:49:03.920
[Guest]: And Nehru's peace overtures to Pakistan were heavily criticized in Bengal.

00:49:03.920 --> 00:49:12.280
[Guest]: They were very unpopular and, I mean, as expected, they were also very unpopular with the Hindu

00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:14.280
[Guest]: right, with the RSS.

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:19.520
[Guest]: And so the RSS news magazine was criticizing him heavily.

00:49:19.520 --> 00:49:28.520
[Guest]: Many right-leaning public figures such as Mukherjee and, you know, someone like the

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:37.080
[Guest]: Hindu Mahasabha leader, Mahant Digvijayanath, were kind of clamoring for some sort of stern

00:49:37.080 --> 00:49:39.520
[Guest]: action against Pakistan.

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:44.680
[Guest]: And this kind of demand for stern action saw wide echo everywhere, even within the Congress

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:45.680
[Guest]: Party.

00:49:45.680 --> 00:49:54.600
[Guest]: There are letters from Nehru who suspects that this kind of viewpoint is being encouraged

00:49:54.600 --> 00:49:56.280
[Guest]: by Patel.

00:49:56.280 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: And so finally he kind of demands action, and obviously action is taken and a pre-censorship

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:05.720
[Guest]: order is passed.

00:50:05.720 --> 00:50:11.840
[Guest]: And the Brij Bhushan, who's the sort of printer and publisher of the organized NKR Malkani,

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:17.200
[Guest]: who's then the editor, again take the matter up to the Supreme Court and a kind of petition

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:18.200
[Guest]: is filed.

00:50:18.200 --> 00:50:24.520
[Guest]: And both cases are heard kind of concurrently in the Supreme Court, which finally gives

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:30.720
[Guest]: out its judgment in May, and they're both now quite well-known cases, Brij Bhushan versus

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:34.840
[Guest]: the state of Delhi and Ramesh Thapar versus the state of Madras.

00:50:34.840 --> 00:50:43.280
[Guest]: And the court's judgment basically lays out quite clearly that the ability of the state

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:48.520
[Guest]: to abridge the right to free speech was limited to the exceptions that had already been written

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:54.600
[Guest]: into the Constitution, which were libel, slander, defamation, contempt of court, or undermining

00:50:54.600 --> 00:50:56.760
[Guest]: the security of the state.

00:50:56.760 --> 00:51:04.080
[Guest]: But the undermining of the security of the state had to create, essentially was quite

00:51:04.080 --> 00:51:05.080
[Guest]: a high standard.

00:51:05.080 --> 00:51:11.560
[Guest]: It had to be undermined to the extent where disorder was of such a magnitude that it imperiled

00:51:11.560 --> 00:51:16.600
[Guest]: the security of the state or it had the potential to overthrow the state.

00:51:16.600 --> 00:51:20.520
[Guest]: And obviously, this did not reach that standard.

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:27.840
[Guest]: So the court not only countermanded both orders, it also held the relevant parts of the legislations

00:51:27.840 --> 00:51:34.320
[Guest]: that we use, the Public Safety and Public Security Acts, to be ultra-virus.

00:51:34.320 --> 00:51:46.160
[Guest]: And that kind of really threw the government's point off because Patel obviously, as he told

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:51.640
[Guest]: Nehru, it kind of knocks the bottom line out of our ability to really control the press.

00:51:51.640 --> 00:51:57.300
[Guest]: But for Nehru, it was an even bigger problem because he thought that this was something

00:51:57.300 --> 00:52:05.080
[Guest]: being done to undermine his peace over Church Pakistan or to, in a way, for example, he

00:52:05.080 --> 00:52:09.880
[Guest]: writes to Raj Gopalchari and he tells him, all of this is propaganda to try and push

00:52:09.880 --> 00:52:12.200
[Guest]: and bully me into war.

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:14.800
[Guest]: And it's a war that he doesn't want to have.

00:52:14.800 --> 00:52:21.520
[Guest]: And it's curious to note that this is a demand that is also made within certain sections

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:24.280
[Guest]: of the Congress Party and his government.

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:31.840
[Guest]: Because eventually when his finance minister, John Mathai, resigns, John Mathai becomes

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:36.880
[Guest]: one of the first people really to publicly describe Nehru's policies towards Pakistan

00:52:36.880 --> 00:52:39.000
[Guest]: as appeasement.

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:46.280
[Guest]: And he becomes the kind of first, one of the first users of that term.

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:51.640
[Guest]: And for Nehru, this sort of criticism of his Pakistan policy, he sees it as effectively

00:52:51.640 --> 00:52:57.000
[Guest]: a tool being used to undermine his overture to Pakistan.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:03.000
[Guest]: He suspects that there is support for that position within the Congress.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:11.280
[Guest]: He, as I note in the book, he berates Patel, telling him that his actions haven't been

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:12.280
[Guest]: enough.

00:53:12.280 --> 00:53:17.920
[Guest]: And I quote, Nehru obviously writes to Patel, not completely satisfied with what is going

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:18.920
[Guest]: on.

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:23.200
[Guest]: I think we have taken up far too lenient an attitude towards those in India who encourage

00:53:23.200 --> 00:53:26.120
[Guest]: this communal feeling of hatred and violence.

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:31.480
[Guest]: The Hindu Mahasabha talks about Akhand Bharat, which is a direct incentive to conflict.

00:53:31.480 --> 00:53:35.120
[Guest]: The belief that retaliation is a suitable method to deal with Pakistan or what happens

00:53:35.120 --> 00:53:36.960
[Guest]: in Pakistan is growing.

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:40.560
[Guest]: That is the surest way to ruin for India and Pakistan.

00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:49.200
[Guest]: And just, I mean, even Patel, who has self-confessedly been deferring to Nehru on this matter, is

00:53:49.200 --> 00:53:52.360
[Guest]: kind of taken aback by Nehru's criticism.

00:53:52.360 --> 00:53:56.800
[Guest]: And he notes, again, I quote, action has been circumscribed only by the provisions of the

00:53:56.800 --> 00:54:00.200
[Guest]: law as interpreted by legal advisors and the high courts.

00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:04.200
[Guest]: We put thousands in jail and adopted a policy of release only after we were continually

00:54:04.200 --> 00:54:07.240
[Guest]: attacked on the score of maintaining civil liberties.

00:54:07.240 --> 00:54:11.240
[Guest]: And then he reminds Nehru, we are now faced with a constitution which guarantees fundamental

00:54:11.240 --> 00:54:16.400
[Guest]: rights, right of association, right of free movement, free expression and personal liberty,

00:54:16.400 --> 00:54:19.240
[Guest]: which further circumscribe the action we can take.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:24.220
[Guest]: That means that for every executive action, there must be legal justification.

00:54:24.220 --> 00:54:27.760
[Guest]: If within these limits, you feel that our policy towards communal organizations has

00:54:27.760 --> 00:54:33.000
[Guest]: been lenient, steps can certainly be taken in the manner you may suggest.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:41.240
[Guest]: So we, I mean, this exchange is a kind of good indication of how seriously this sort

00:54:41.240 --> 00:54:50.960
[Guest]: of criticism of his Pakistan policy was affecting Nehru or how, indeed, how determined he was

00:54:50.960 --> 00:54:58.400
[Guest]: to find a way to kind of, if not, you know, crush it, at least to, at least to really

00:54:58.400 --> 00:55:02.640
[Guest]: smother it as, as far as he could.

00:55:02.640 --> 00:55:11.600
[Guest]: And then of course, the second point of pain was the question of reservations, which had.

00:55:11.600 --> 00:55:15.360
[Amit Varma]: But can I, while we're on the subject, can I ask a sort of a tangential question which

00:55:15.360 --> 00:55:21.040
[Amit Varma]: arose from something you wrote during this time, one, I just want to sort of point out

00:55:21.040 --> 00:55:25.360
[Amit Varma]: to my listeners, some of the dates involved, because, you know, Tripudaman, you mentioned

00:55:25.360 --> 00:55:31.160
[Amit Varma]: about how you were sort of taken in by the phrase of a narrative going as fast as a bullet.

00:55:31.160 --> 00:55:35.680
[Amit Varma]: And I was, my jaw dropped open when I saw how fast the courts actually worked in that

00:55:35.680 --> 00:55:36.680
[Amit Varma]: time.

00:55:36.680 --> 00:55:41.720
[Amit Varma]: Like you point out that, you know, the constitution is, it comes on January 26, 1950.

00:55:41.720 --> 00:55:47.800
[Amit Varma]: On Feb 6, these communist detainees in Bombay file a case and they are freed on Feb 8, in

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:48.800
[Amit Varma]: two days they are free.

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:53.520
[Amit Varma]: And on Feb 11, the other communist detainees in Salem start their whole thing, which ends

00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:57.600
[Amit Varma]: with, you know, the deaths of the 22 people.

00:55:57.600 --> 00:56:03.760
[Amit Varma]: And that gets a crossroads to sort of, you know, write about that and Nehru defends the

00:56:03.760 --> 00:56:04.760
[Amit Varma]: state action.

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:08.000
[Amit Varma]: At which point I was struck by this quote by Jayaprakash Narayan.

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And if you forget who is talking about who, there are echoes of this, which reverberate

00:56:13.160 --> 00:56:17.920
[Amit Varma]: to this time where Jayaprakash Narayan says of Nehru, quote, the prime minister of India

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:21.920
[Amit Varma]: talked in the language of dictators when he maintained that we had to choose between security

00:56:21.920 --> 00:56:27.760
[Amit Varma]: of the state and freedom of the individual, we must choose the former, stop quote.

00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And later on, KR Malkani, the editor of The Organizer, which is ERSS mag, which, you know,

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:38.240
[Amit Varma]: defends the case against the pre-censorship order against it, he writes, quote, to threaten

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:43.120
[Amit Varma]: the liberty of the press for the sole offense of non-conformity to official view in each

00:56:43.120 --> 00:56:48.560
[Amit Varma]: and every matter may be a handy tool for tyrants, but is only a crippling curtailment of civil

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:50.400
[Amit Varma]: liberties in a free democracy.

00:56:50.400 --> 00:56:55.000
[Amit Varma]: A government can always learn more from bona fide criticism of independent thinking citizens

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:59.720
[Amit Varma]: than the fulsome flattery of charlatans, stop quote.

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:04.240
[Amit Varma]: And later on, you, in referring to the case by The Organizer, which was, you know, fought

00:57:04.240 --> 00:57:09.960
[Amit Varma]: by NC Chatterjee, you write about the case, quote, this case in itself was curious, succinct

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:14.880
[Amit Varma]: and informative, and an example of a great tradition of liberal thought within the Hindu

00:57:14.880 --> 00:57:19.360
[Amit Varma]: nationalist movement that now seems to have been lost and forgotten, stop quote.

00:57:19.360 --> 00:57:23.300
[Amit Varma]: And you didn't elaborate on this in the book because the book is about something else entirely.

00:57:23.300 --> 00:57:28.480
[Amit Varma]: But I nevertheless want to go on this tangent and ask you about this tradition of liberal

00:57:28.480 --> 00:57:30.920
[Amit Varma]: thought within the Hindu nationalist movement.

00:57:30.920 --> 00:57:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, why is it lost and forgotten, as you describe it?

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.880
[Guest]: What is your sense of it?

00:57:37.880 --> 00:57:43.120
[Guest]: It's interesting that you mentioned that because there were several quotes, of course, there's

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:46.680
[Guest]: that one by Malkani.

00:57:46.680 --> 00:57:50.820
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are many quotes by Shyamaprasad Mukherjee, where he is very eloquently defending

00:57:50.820 --> 00:57:54.160
[Amit Varma]: the right to free speech and the fundamental rights and all of that.

00:57:54.160 --> 00:57:59.120
[Amit Varma]: But I'm more interested by what you term the liberal tradition within the sort of the Hindu

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:00.360
[Amit Varma]: nationalist movement.

00:58:00.360 --> 00:58:01.360
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:58:01.360 --> 00:58:07.640
[Guest]: So, I mean, I mentioned it in the context of this, because it's interesting that both

00:58:07.640 --> 00:58:15.760
[Guest]: Crossroads and the Organizer basically criticize the Nehru government along similar sort of

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:16.760
[Guest]: pathways.

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:24.280
[Guest]: They criticize them for being heavy handed, for trampling on civil liberties, for not

00:58:24.280 --> 00:58:29.000
[Guest]: taking oppositional views on board, for encouraging ideological conformity.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:35.600
[Guest]: And they criticize them using a kind of terminology that we would now recognize as quite distinctly

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:36.600
[Guest]: liberal.

00:58:36.600 --> 00:58:44.360
[Guest]: So, respect for individual freedom, respect for the right to free speech, tolerance of

00:58:44.360 --> 00:58:46.440
[Guest]: dissent and criticism.

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:50.200
[Guest]: These are profoundly, profoundly liberal virtues.

00:58:50.200 --> 00:58:55.400
[Guest]: And this argument is made by K. R. Malkani in his columns.

00:58:55.400 --> 00:59:00.360
[Guest]: This argument is made by N. C. Chatterjee, who again, by the way, is a former Hindu Mahasabha

00:59:00.360 --> 00:59:04.240
[Guest]: stalwart in his submissions in court.

00:59:04.240 --> 00:59:10.640
[Guest]: And this argument is made by Shyamaprasad Mukherjee in his interventions in Parliament.

00:59:10.640 --> 00:59:15.360
[Guest]: And all sort of frame their arguments in these terms.

00:59:15.360 --> 00:59:21.640
[Guest]: Now, there is, I'm sure a lot of people would say that that's just what was expedient at

00:59:21.640 --> 00:59:23.200
[Guest]: the time.

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:29.040
[Guest]: And this is just a matter of kind of using the constitutional defenses that you have

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:30.080
[Guest]: to have your own way.

00:59:30.080 --> 00:59:35.320
[Guest]: And that's perfectly, I'm sure there was an element of that.

00:59:35.320 --> 00:59:41.720
[Guest]: But equally, it to me looks like a kind of distinct liberal tradition, because you have

00:59:41.720 --> 00:59:48.880
[Guest]: all the kind of, both the political element of it, and the kind of, how should I put it,

00:59:48.880 --> 00:59:55.400
[Guest]: the ideological element, because for want of a better word, I mean, the organizer does

00:59:55.400 --> 00:59:59.280
[Guest]: represent the official viewpoint of the RSS.

00:59:59.280 --> 01:00:06.720
[Guest]: And what comes across to me is a kind of element of liberal thought, which should realistically

01:00:06.720 --> 01:00:13.400
[Guest]: have been nourished and encouraged, rather than clamped down on.

01:00:13.400 --> 01:00:18.880
[Guest]: And that's, I think, one of the more unfortunate parts of the whole story of the First Amendment

01:00:18.880 --> 01:00:28.800
[Guest]: is the fact that this sort of narrow dispensation is willing to countenance the use of distinctly

01:00:28.800 --> 01:00:35.840
[Guest]: illiberal legal and constitutional tools to clamp down on a kind of ideological position

01:00:35.840 --> 01:00:44.000
[Guest]: that, while kind of discredited in the Narrowvian era, did nevertheless consistently enjoy a

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:48.720
[Guest]: sort of reasonable modicum of public support.

01:00:48.720 --> 01:00:59.000
[Guest]: And I think that's something that as a statesman, he should have seen through, or should, I

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:02.840
[Guest]: mean, it's a kind of tradition that I feel should have been encouraged.

01:01:02.840 --> 01:01:10.400
[Guest]: Obviously, it's a kind of tradition that is lost because the ideological and political

01:01:10.400 --> 01:01:17.640
[Guest]: successes of these people who are now, I mean, if you ever go to, if you ever see the inside

01:01:17.640 --> 01:01:23.720
[Guest]: of a BJP office, you will always have a huge portrait of Shyam Prasad Mukherjee.

01:01:23.720 --> 01:01:33.680
[Guest]: But even within that stream of thought, people have really forgotten or maybe deliberately

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:42.600
[Guest]: ignored the fact that Mukherjee was not the kind of bigoted authoritarian figure that

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:44.720
[Guest]: people might imagine him to be.

01:01:44.720 --> 01:01:52.040
[Guest]: He was, in many ways, a sort of textbook case of classical liberalism.

01:01:52.040 --> 01:01:58.880
[Guest]: So that again, that's again, a very, very interesting part of the story with tremendous

01:01:58.880 --> 01:01:59.880
[Guest]: contemporary relevance.

01:01:59.880 --> 01:02:00.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:02:00.880 --> 01:02:04.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, even before reading your book, you know, whenever I've come across like the Mukherjee

01:02:04.040 --> 01:02:08.200
[Amit Varma]: Nehru debates in the sort of Constituent Assembly debates and the debates they had during the

01:02:08.200 --> 01:02:13.320
[Amit Varma]: first amendment, it always struck me that, you know, if you just reproduce a dialogue

01:02:13.320 --> 01:02:17.480
[Amit Varma]: and you blank out the names, it would appear that it is definitely Shyam Prasad Mukherjee

01:02:17.480 --> 01:02:24.480
[Amit Varma]: who is a great liberal and a Nehru who is a, you know, a dictatorial despot, as it were.

01:02:24.480 --> 01:02:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And here also, it strikes me that like one thing which is, you know, I think certainly

01:02:27.800 --> 01:02:34.320
[Amit Varma]: true is that it's very easy to appear virtuous in opposition, because you can say whatever,

01:02:34.320 --> 01:02:37.600
[Amit Varma]: but you know, you can do all the signaling in the right way.

01:02:37.600 --> 01:02:40.440
[Amit Varma]: It's like, we don't even have to go as far back as Shyam Prasad.

01:02:40.440 --> 01:02:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Even pre the 2014 elections, you know, Narendra Modi was making a lot of noises which would

01:02:45.840 --> 01:02:50.240
[Amit Varma]: please liberals, especially about downsizing government, minimum government, maximum governance

01:02:50.240 --> 01:02:53.880
[Amit Varma]: and the government has no business to be in business and all of those things.

01:02:53.880 --> 01:02:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, his actions have gone in the opposite direction.

01:02:56.760 --> 01:03:00.280
[Amit Varma]: But he was making a lot of noises even, you know, Salman's source of the Congress was

01:03:00.280 --> 01:03:01.360
[Amit Varma]: on my show.

01:03:01.360 --> 01:03:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And he said that even he approved of a lot of the rhetoric.

01:03:04.560 --> 01:03:09.480
[Amit Varma]: So when Modi came to power, even Salman in the Congress was cautiously optimistic that

01:03:09.480 --> 01:03:12.320
[Amit Varma]: he'll actually deliver on some of those things.

01:03:12.320 --> 01:03:15.720
[Amit Varma]: But the imperatives of actually being in government seemed to me to be quite different from the

01:03:15.720 --> 01:03:21.120
[Amit Varma]: imperatives of, you know, being in opposition, for example, you know, when you are in that

01:03:21.120 --> 01:03:27.520
[Amit Varma]: position of responsibility, where you have to sort of juggle 100 different things and,

01:03:27.520 --> 01:03:31.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, and actually get things done, is there then a battle between pragmatism and

01:03:31.840 --> 01:03:36.840
[Amit Varma]: principles which plays out where, you know, a Sardar Patel can say that it is okay for

01:03:36.840 --> 01:03:41.320
[Amit Varma]: you to say whatever you want sitting where you are, but I have the responsibility of

01:03:41.320 --> 01:03:44.320
[Amit Varma]: being the Home Minister and therefore security does matter.

01:03:44.320 --> 01:03:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And you can leave your security freedom debate elsewhere, but I have to keep the country

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:49.000
[Amit Varma]: together.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:52.600
[Amit Varma]: And these are, of course, in the fraught times after there has been so much trouble bringing

01:03:52.600 --> 01:03:55.000
[Amit Varma]: the country together in the first place.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:59.320
[Amit Varma]: So is that always a constant tussle where those who are in the opposition will always

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:04.720
[Amit Varma]: seem more virtuous than those in the government because you are judging those in the government

01:04:04.720 --> 01:04:08.440
[Amit Varma]: by their actions, while you're judging those in opposition by their words?

01:04:08.440 --> 01:04:12.720
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, there's to a certain extent, that's true.

01:04:12.720 --> 01:04:19.320
[Guest]: And there are, Patel often makes the case that as the kind of person responsible for

01:04:19.320 --> 01:04:24.520
[Guest]: the nation's security, there are things that just need to be done.

01:04:24.520 --> 01:04:30.160
[Guest]: But equally, I think it's, there is more happening than that.

01:04:30.160 --> 01:04:36.040
[Guest]: And the reason that comes through with the kind of internal opposition that is triggered

01:04:36.040 --> 01:04:44.920
[Guest]: within the Congress Party and that comes from the sort of indications that things are not,

01:04:44.920 --> 01:04:49.600
[Guest]: obviously there's often a gap between the ideals that, you know, nations and governments

01:04:49.600 --> 01:04:54.640
[Guest]: and political parties profess and the imperatives of government.

01:04:54.640 --> 01:05:01.840
[Guest]: But that things are not really going as had been imagined, that there are plenty of indications

01:05:01.840 --> 01:05:02.840
[Guest]: to it.

01:05:02.840 --> 01:05:07.880
[Guest]: Those indications come from the speaker at some point where he writes to Nehru, for example,

01:05:07.880 --> 01:05:16.120
[Guest]: to say, you know, express his disapproval of the frequent recourse to the use of presidential

01:05:16.120 --> 01:05:18.000
[Guest]: ordinances.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:25.720
[Guest]: It comes from sort of dissident congressmen, like figures like Acharya Kriplani.

01:05:25.720 --> 01:05:30.240
[Guest]: Now, of course, people can make the case that, you know, Kriplani was upset because he hadn't

01:05:30.240 --> 01:05:35.080
[Guest]: been made a minister and he hadn't, you know, won the election to the Congress presidency

01:05:35.080 --> 01:05:39.160
[Guest]: and he was kind of sidelined.

01:05:39.160 --> 01:05:42.720
[Guest]: And perhaps some of his criticism did come from there.

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:49.280
[Guest]: But if we are to kind of constantly simply assume an ulterior motive or a motive driven

01:05:49.280 --> 01:05:55.120
[Guest]: solely by realpolitik, I think that would also be a bit unfair.

01:05:55.120 --> 01:06:02.600
[Guest]: And the fact that perhaps it was easy for Malkani and Mukherjee, etc., to deploy the

01:06:02.600 --> 01:06:08.840
[Guest]: kind of rhetoric of liberalism while not being saddled with the responsibility of government.

01:06:08.840 --> 01:06:14.520
[Guest]: And in truth, we can never really have a firm answer to that question.

01:06:14.520 --> 01:06:19.400
[Guest]: But there are plenty of indications that even within the Congress, there was disquiet at

01:06:19.400 --> 01:06:21.040
[Guest]: the way things were being done.

01:06:21.040 --> 01:06:26.480
[Guest]: And you get that from quite senior, quite pivotal figures, from Rajendra Prasad, from

01:06:26.480 --> 01:06:38.280
[Guest]: Acharya Kriplani, from G. V. Mavlankar, and indeed from some dissidents who kind of speak

01:06:38.280 --> 01:06:39.600
[Guest]: up during the debate.

01:06:39.600 --> 01:06:45.840
[Guest]: And some of the things that are often said both by Nehru and by other figures within

01:06:45.840 --> 01:06:53.240
[Guest]: the Congress establishment would, I mean, quite shocking, at least surprising if not

01:06:53.240 --> 01:06:58.400
[Guest]: shocking to read because, I mean, you have figures like Hare Krishna Mehta who basically

01:06:58.400 --> 01:07:06.080
[Guest]: tells Nehru that the real culprits are actually things such as the right to equality itself,

01:07:06.080 --> 01:07:07.960
[Guest]: which shouldn't be there.

01:07:07.960 --> 01:07:14.960
[Guest]: So there is a kind of disquiet within the Congress which would, I think, give some credence

01:07:14.960 --> 01:07:22.840
[Guest]: at least or at least some reason for us to give figures such as Mukherjee a kind of,

01:07:22.840 --> 01:07:27.960
[Guest]: if not 100% of our indulgence, at least, you know, 50% of our indulgence.

01:07:27.960 --> 01:07:31.440
[Amit Varma]: And also, I mean, Mukherjee was part of the cabinet and he did quit in protest.

01:07:31.440 --> 01:07:36.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, he could just have stayed a minister had he wanted.

