[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with the historian Tripudaman Singh about his fabulous book where the narrative

01:09:05.680 --> 01:09:09.640
[Amit Varma]: goes as fast as a bullet, 16 Stormy Days.

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:14.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, while Tripudaman's book, the narrative does go as fast as a bullet, my

01:09:14.120 --> 01:09:17.680
[Amit Varma]: show is a little bit more leisurely, which is why we have reached the break and we have

01:09:17.680 --> 01:09:22.680
[Amit Varma]: only finished two of the three fault lines that kind of led to the first amendment being

01:09:22.680 --> 01:09:25.760
[Amit Varma]: felt necessary by Jawaharlal Nehru.

01:09:25.760 --> 01:09:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Two of them to quickly recap are, of course, that he wanted to enact zamindari reforms

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:35.120
[Amit Varma]: and that was struck down by the Bihar High Court and was, you know, there was litigation

01:09:35.120 --> 01:09:39.880
[Amit Varma]: in other places and the Bihar High Court struck it down on the grounds of the right to equality,

01:09:39.880 --> 01:09:43.520
[Amit Varma]: but it was also sort of challenged on the right to property.

01:09:43.520 --> 01:09:49.120
[Amit Varma]: And even though experts felt that you could have redrafted those laws and got them through

01:09:49.120 --> 01:09:51.920
[Amit Varma]: and made them constitutional, Nehru was a man in a hurry.

01:09:51.920 --> 01:09:54.680
[Amit Varma]: The second, of course, is the free speech laws.

01:09:54.680 --> 01:10:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Now we think of Article 19.1, I certainly do, as, you know, being, you know, the opposite

01:10:00.120 --> 01:10:05.120
[Amit Varma]: of the pristine First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution, which sanctifies free speech,

01:10:05.120 --> 01:10:07.360
[Amit Varma]: but in this particular case, it has a bunch of caveats.

01:10:07.360 --> 01:10:13.220
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that the original constitution enacted on 26 Jan 1950 had some

01:10:13.220 --> 01:10:17.560
[Amit Varma]: of these caveats, but the First Amendment brought in a bunch more like public order

01:10:17.560 --> 01:10:23.080
[Amit Varma]: and so on, which can be left open to the interpretation of governments.

01:10:23.080 --> 01:10:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And there was a fault line there because he tried, he banned Crossroads, which was a communist

01:10:27.840 --> 01:10:33.840
[Amit Varma]: magazine, and he tried to impose pre-censorship on the organizer, the RSS magazine.

01:10:33.840 --> 01:10:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Both of those fine parties went to court and the law moved a little bit quicker than it

01:10:39.400 --> 01:10:41.240
[Amit Varma]: does today, and both of them won.

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:45.360
[Amit Varma]: So Nehru's also now thinking, okay, not just right to property, not just right to equality,

01:10:45.360 --> 01:10:46.520
[Amit Varma]: there's also right to free speech.

01:10:46.520 --> 01:10:50.320
[Amit Varma]: Where's the third fault line to put them and tell me a bit about how that came about?

01:10:50.320 --> 01:10:51.320
[Guest]: Sure.

01:10:51.320 --> 01:10:55.960
[Guest]: Just, I mean, just before I move on to that, a quick kind of detour back to what we were

01:10:55.960 --> 01:11:01.840
[Guest]: talking about was, I think, when I mentioned that there was disquiet within the kind of

01:11:01.840 --> 01:11:06.320
[Guest]: Congress establishment as well, I think the most important indication of this, as early

01:11:06.320 --> 01:11:15.280
[Guest]: as April 1950, comes from Sardar Patel, whose letter to Nehru I quoted, where he, you know,

01:11:15.280 --> 01:11:20.600
[Guest]: kind of reminds him of the fact that whatever they have to do has to be within constitutional

01:11:20.600 --> 01:11:22.040
[Guest]: bounds.

01:11:22.040 --> 01:11:31.880
[Guest]: And now Patel is quite ambivalent about his commitment to expansive free speech, and he

01:11:31.880 --> 01:11:36.840
[Guest]: obviously tells, he once does note to Nehru that they will have to consider amendments

01:11:36.840 --> 01:11:40.520
[Guest]: to the constitution at some point, or that the right to free speech was the result of

01:11:40.520 --> 01:11:43.240
[Guest]: idealistic exuberance.

01:11:43.240 --> 01:11:48.840
[Guest]: But Patel's letter is also a kind of, its tone is very sarcastic.

01:11:48.840 --> 01:11:53.080
[Guest]: It notes things which, I mean, it's basically telling Nehru things that, you know, you would

01:11:53.080 --> 01:11:58.880
[Guest]: expect a grade six student studying civics to know.

01:11:58.880 --> 01:12:07.960
[Guest]: And so I would see that as a kind of indication that even Patel did somewhere think that what

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:14.520
[Guest]: Nehru was asking him to do was to essentially set aside constitutional bounds and contemplate

01:12:14.520 --> 01:12:18.040
[Guest]: action that would quite clearly breach constitutional norms.

01:12:18.040 --> 01:12:24.760
[Guest]: So I think knowing that we have to be willing to give some benefit of the doubt to figures

01:12:24.760 --> 01:12:29.160
[Guest]: like Malkani and Mukherjee, obviously, we can't, we can never quite know what they would

01:12:29.160 --> 01:12:34.600
[Guest]: have done in government, but we can give them some benefit of the doubt to say that the

01:12:34.600 --> 01:12:38.760
[Guest]: position that they were taking up were not simply the result of real politics, but also

01:12:38.760 --> 01:12:40.360
[Guest]: of some sort of ideological conviction.

01:12:40.360 --> 01:12:45.580
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I should clarify that when I phrased that earlier question, I did not mean

01:12:45.580 --> 01:12:49.720
[Amit Varma]: to cynically imply that, oh, in opposition, you will be virtuous only because you're in

01:12:49.720 --> 01:12:52.080
[Amit Varma]: opposition and vice versa.

01:12:52.080 --> 01:12:54.720
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, there are complex currents in the affairs of men.

01:12:54.720 --> 01:12:58.920
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, people do things for multifactorial reasons, many of which they themselves might

01:12:58.920 --> 01:13:00.400
[Amit Varma]: not be aware of.

01:13:00.400 --> 01:13:05.200
[Amit Varma]: So while I think in general, we should take people at face value unless we have reason

01:13:05.200 --> 01:13:06.840
[Amit Varma]: to believe otherwise.

01:13:06.840 --> 01:13:11.040
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, as a friend of mine, like saying, assume goodwill.

01:13:11.040 --> 01:13:16.520
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, there's no reason to do otherwise with either Malkani or Shyamaprasad Mukherjee

01:13:16.520 --> 01:13:22.280
[Amit Varma]: or Jayaprakash Narayan or, you know, any of the eminences who kind of oppose the amendment.

01:13:22.280 --> 01:13:26.680
[Amit Varma]: And while we are on the subject, I'll quickly quote from your book to show what a wide range

01:13:26.680 --> 01:13:32.800
[Amit Varma]: of opposition there was to Nehru at this time, where you write, quote, Hindu nationalists

01:13:32.800 --> 01:13:33.800
[Amit Varma]: like S.P.

01:13:33.800 --> 01:13:34.800
[Amit Varma]: Mukherjee and M.R.

01:13:34.800 --> 01:13:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Jaikar, Gandhian stalwarts like Acharya Kripalani, committed socialists like Shibbanlal Saxena

01:13:39.920 --> 01:13:44.640
[Amit Varma]: and Jayaprakash Narayan, conscientious Congress rebels like H.V.

01:13:44.640 --> 01:13:47.800
[Amit Varma]: Kamant, Svanandan Sahay and K.K.

01:13:47.800 --> 01:13:51.040
[Amit Varma]: Bhattacharya, jurists like Pranath Mehra and M.C.

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Chagla, press associations, editors, lawyers and businessmen, men whose ideological and

01:13:56.560 --> 01:14:02.440
[Amit Varma]: editorial successes today might scarcely believe, but would do well to remember that their predecessors

01:14:02.440 --> 01:14:05.000
[Amit Varma]: held the views they did, stop quote.

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:10.640
[Amit Varma]: And while you brought Patel in, I was also kind of, you know, before we get to the sort

01:14:10.640 --> 01:14:14.920
[Amit Varma]: of the third fault line, I was also struck by a quote about Nehru and Patel, which I

01:14:14.920 --> 01:14:16.360
[Amit Varma]: thought I'll ask you about later.

01:14:16.360 --> 01:14:20.480
[Amit Varma]: But as we are on the subject now, where you wrote, quote, their commitment to civil liberties

01:14:20.480 --> 01:14:25.640
[Amit Varma]: and individual freedom or the lack thereof represented a rare consensus between the two

01:14:25.640 --> 01:14:29.600
[Amit Varma]: giants of Indian politics, stop quote, who would have thunk.

01:14:29.600 --> 01:14:35.800
[Amit Varma]: And I guess their skepticism towards fundamental rights, which, you know, as you pointed out,

01:14:35.800 --> 01:14:41.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, Patel at one point said reflected quote, idealistic exuberance, I guess, would

01:14:41.040 --> 01:14:42.680
[Amit Varma]: have come for different reasons.

01:14:42.680 --> 01:14:46.480
[Amit Varma]: For Patel, it would have been that look, I have a tough job to do, the security at stake

01:14:46.480 --> 01:14:50.760
[Amit Varma]: there is, you know, we take the nation for granted today at the time Patel was Home Minister,

01:14:50.760 --> 01:14:55.840
[Amit Varma]: he had just managed to cobble it together, almost in a new act of imperialism as it were.

01:14:55.840 --> 01:14:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And the priority was to hold it together and the rights were in the way.

01:14:58.800 --> 01:15:04.200
[Amit Varma]: While for Nehru, to be honest, he had been consistent all his political life about his

01:15:04.200 --> 01:15:08.760
[Amit Varma]: values being social progressivism and all of the things that went along with that, like

01:15:08.760 --> 01:15:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Zamindari reforms and so on.

01:15:10.840 --> 01:15:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And again, the constitution was sort of an impediment to that.

01:15:15.760 --> 01:15:21.320
[Amit Varma]: Is that sort of a correct characterization that they were coming from a different place,

01:15:21.320 --> 01:15:24.400
[Amit Varma]: which was, you know, and the constitution was a separate thing.

01:15:24.400 --> 01:15:30.880
[Amit Varma]: Today we talk about the constitution and the values it embodies as almost holy and sacramental,

01:15:30.880 --> 01:15:35.500
[Amit Varma]: but in those tumultuous times, it would not have had the place it did, even in the minds

01:15:35.500 --> 01:15:36.720
[Guest]: of those who drafted it.

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:37.720
[Guest]: You're right.

01:15:37.720 --> 01:15:43.040
[Guest]: I mean, there was a kind of sense of consensus between them on the constitution, but they

01:15:43.040 --> 01:15:47.960
[Guest]: did approach it, as you rightly point out, from different angles.

01:15:47.960 --> 01:15:53.360
[Guest]: And perhaps, yes, it didn't really have the kind of same sense of sanctity that it seems

01:15:53.360 --> 01:15:58.160
[Guest]: to have now, at least, I mean, I'm not sure how much sanctity it really has, but at least

01:15:58.160 --> 01:16:01.880
[Guest]: in the public mind, that kind of sanctity attaches to it.

01:16:01.880 --> 01:16:09.360
[Guest]: But it's interesting to note that when the constitution first comes into force, everyone

01:16:09.360 --> 01:16:13.360
[Guest]: gives a statement saying, yes, you know, we have to maintain the sanctity of the constitution,

01:16:13.360 --> 01:16:15.120
[Guest]: et cetera, et cetera.

01:16:15.120 --> 01:16:19.480
[Guest]: But on the other hand, when the amendment finally reaches parliament and it's criticized

01:16:19.480 --> 01:16:24.720
[Guest]: for the fact that it's being amended so soon without a general election, you know, by an

01:16:24.720 --> 01:16:34.000
[Guest]: unelected body, Nehru makes a kind of response by saying that since we were competent to

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:38.560
[Guest]: make it, we should be competent to amend it as well.

01:16:38.560 --> 01:16:48.400
[Guest]: And I think that kind of just supports what you said, really, that they saw it as almost

01:16:48.400 --> 01:16:56.200
[Guest]: as something that was there as a kind of vehicle towards a particular end, perhaps rather than

01:16:56.200 --> 01:16:58.400
[Guest]: an end in itself.

01:16:58.400 --> 01:17:06.200
[Guest]: And that end, nobody was quite sure of, because for Nehru that end represented a kind of particular

01:17:06.200 --> 01:17:08.880
[Guest]: kind of social progressivism.

01:17:08.880 --> 01:17:13.600
[Guest]: For others, it represented a kind of, I think, especially for Rajendra Prasad, it represented

01:17:13.600 --> 01:17:17.140
[Guest]: a kind of stable property order.

01:17:17.140 --> 01:17:23.960
[Guest]: And for quite others, it represented a kind of liberal democracy as they had come to expect

01:17:23.960 --> 01:17:29.000
[Guest]: by looking at what had happened in Europe and America.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:36.600
[Guest]: And so nobody, I think, because there was no real kind of consensus on what exactly

01:17:36.600 --> 01:17:41.840
[Guest]: the end was, people saw it as a vehicle towards a particular end, but they didn't quite agree

01:17:41.840 --> 01:17:44.720
[Amit Varma]: on what that end really was.

01:17:44.720 --> 01:17:49.640
[Amit Varma]: So can I ask you a broader question now that I'd actually save for the end, but again,

01:17:49.640 --> 01:17:54.220
[Amit Varma]: we are sort of on the subject, which is, I mean, two broader questions, really.

01:17:54.220 --> 01:18:00.860
[Amit Varma]: And the first one is about just this notion of what India should be, sort of the competing

01:18:00.860 --> 01:18:05.120
[Amit Varma]: early ideas of India, which can even merge into one idea of India, you know, as you've

01:18:05.120 --> 01:18:07.400
[Amit Varma]: shown in your book, they can mean different things.

01:18:07.400 --> 01:18:11.760
[Amit Varma]: And one is, of course, the sort of democracy Nehru had in mind, which would aim at a particular

01:18:11.760 --> 01:18:16.580
[Amit Varma]: kind of social equality and social justice, and so on, and all of those things.

01:18:16.580 --> 01:18:22.140
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, a constitutional republic, where you would be bound by certain rules

01:18:22.140 --> 01:18:29.460
[Amit Varma]: of the game, which would constrain the behavior of the state and, you know, circumscribe what

01:18:29.460 --> 01:18:31.580
[Amit Varma]: the state could do to its citizens.

01:18:31.580 --> 01:18:36.340
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that at the heart of this, there is an inherent contradiction.

01:18:36.340 --> 01:18:41.860
[Amit Varma]: And that contradiction has very much to do with, you know, how you think of means versus

01:18:41.860 --> 01:18:42.860
[Amit Varma]: ends.

01:18:42.860 --> 01:18:46.940
[Amit Varma]: While where Nehru's thinking was that, look, my ends are that these are the things I want

01:18:46.940 --> 01:18:47.940
[Amit Varma]: to achieve.

01:18:47.940 --> 01:18:49.740
[Amit Varma]: And these are my means of doing so.

01:18:49.740 --> 01:18:53.500
[Amit Varma]: And one could, you know, even argue that even those means are flawed, because they are based

01:18:53.500 --> 01:18:56.220
[Amit Varma]: on top down thinking, and they didn't actually get anywhere.

01:18:56.220 --> 01:19:01.140
[Amit Varma]: But regardless, that could be his way of looking at it, while the constitutional way of thinking

01:19:01.140 --> 01:19:05.180
[Amit Varma]: would be that the means are everything, that you have to protect individual rights, you

01:19:05.180 --> 01:19:10.020
[Amit Varma]: have to respect individual autonomy, the citizen is a master of the state and not the other

01:19:10.020 --> 01:19:11.100
[Amit Varma]: way around.

01:19:11.100 --> 01:19:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's where all the fundamental rights come up.

01:19:14.520 --> 01:19:19.580
[Amit Varma]: So do you think that there is, and to me, it seems that, you know, your book describes

01:19:19.580 --> 01:19:25.060
[Amit Varma]: a period of time where the people in power are at the heart of this conflict, and they

01:19:25.060 --> 01:19:29.300
[Amit Varma]: are choosing their democratic ends over constitutional means.

01:19:29.300 --> 01:19:31.900
[Amit Varma]: And to do this, they're completely subverting the constitution.

01:19:31.900 --> 01:19:37.300
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I really think we, you know, as your book kind of makes explicit, we had a real

01:19:37.300 --> 01:19:40.500
[Amit Varma]: liberal constitution for perhaps 14 months of our history.

01:19:40.500 --> 01:19:44.060
[Amit Varma]: And after that, we didn't, it's a periodical and whoever is in power does whatever the

01:19:44.060 --> 01:19:45.780
[Amit Varma]: hell they want with it.

01:19:45.780 --> 01:19:50.980
[Amit Varma]: So to your end, is this a tragic outcome that the two went in different directions?

01:19:50.980 --> 01:19:55.340
[Amit Varma]: Or is that conflict something that simply cannot be negotiated?

01:19:55.340 --> 01:20:01.460
[Amit Varma]: It's just, you know, between being a democracy, what the popular will of the people is and

01:20:01.460 --> 01:20:02.460
[Amit Varma]: constitutional values per se.

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:07.260
[Guest]: I mean, I think, but at some level, that conflict is kind of inherent in any sort of democratic

01:20:07.260 --> 01:20:16.260
[Guest]: setup, because the temptation to do certain things or to kind of take shortcuts is always

01:20:16.260 --> 01:20:17.260
[Guest]: there.

01:20:17.260 --> 01:20:24.740
[Guest]: And one of the arguments that's often deployed is that, you know, part and parcel of a democratic

01:20:24.740 --> 01:20:28.980
[Guest]: system is to reflect the will of the people.

01:20:28.980 --> 01:20:34.460
[Guest]: And Nehru deploys this argument, I think, in a flawed manner, because obviously there

01:20:34.460 --> 01:20:41.460
[Guest]: has been no democratic mandate yet by, you know, saying that the legislature has to decide

01:20:41.460 --> 01:20:46.940
[Guest]: on matters of social policy and wherever the constitution comes in the way of the will

01:20:46.940 --> 01:20:51.980
[Guest]: of the people, then obviously the constitution has to give way.

01:20:51.980 --> 01:20:58.740
[Guest]: So I don't think you can completely avoid that conflict anywhere.

01:20:58.740 --> 01:21:04.140
[Guest]: But the answers that you reach or the sort of mechanisms that are devised to mediate

01:21:04.140 --> 01:21:09.300
[Guest]: that conflict, I mean, ultimately that's where all of the action is.

01:21:09.300 --> 01:21:17.740
[Guest]: And Nehru's view very much is of a kind that one would, you know, for example, expect somewhere

01:21:17.740 --> 01:21:23.820
[Guest]: in somewhere like Britain, where parliamentary sovereignty is kind of expansive and there

01:21:23.820 --> 01:21:25.140
[Guest]: is no written constitution.

01:21:25.140 --> 01:21:33.300
[Guest]: So whatever parliament does is, you know, ipso facto that it is constitutional, whereas

01:21:33.300 --> 01:21:39.220
[Guest]: a written constitution by its very nature is meant to contain and circumscribe the actions

01:21:39.220 --> 01:21:43.420
[Guest]: of the branches of government or the branches of the state, rather.

01:21:43.420 --> 01:21:51.860
[Guest]: And that's kind of, I recently read political theorist Madhav Khosla's book on the constitution.

01:21:51.860 --> 01:21:56.380
[Guest]: And again, that's one of the arguments that he makes is that one of the reasons that the

01:21:56.380 --> 01:22:04.140
[Guest]: constitution is so lengthy was because they didn't simply want to delineate general principles,

01:22:04.140 --> 01:22:10.420
[Guest]: but to kind of contain and guide the actions of future legislators, judges and politicians

01:22:10.420 --> 01:22:12.060
[Guest]: in a particular direction.

01:22:12.060 --> 01:22:16.100
[Guest]: And that's one of the reasons why the constitution goes into so much detail.

01:22:16.100 --> 01:22:23.660
[Guest]: And it's a point that Mukherjee makes repeatedly when the amendment is introduced into parliament,

01:22:23.660 --> 01:22:28.780
[Guest]: saying that the very fact that if this is what we wanted to do, then we should not have

01:22:28.780 --> 01:22:31.460
[Guest]: had a written constitution in the first place.

01:22:31.460 --> 01:22:37.540
[Guest]: Having a written constitution, especially one as detailed as ours, comes with a set

01:22:37.540 --> 01:22:42.020
[Guest]: of implications, which means that you are constrained in what you can do.

01:22:42.020 --> 01:22:47.860
[Guest]: And yes, there is a kind of system of amendment.

01:22:47.860 --> 01:22:53.780
[Guest]: But even for that system of amendment to be kind of scrupulously followed, you have to

01:22:53.780 --> 01:22:59.780
[Guest]: have an election and two elected houses of parliament.

01:22:59.780 --> 01:23:05.060
[Guest]: And so that conflict can't be avoided, but the conclusions that Nehru came to certainly

01:23:05.060 --> 01:23:06.060
[Guest]: could have been.

01:23:06.060 --> 01:23:11.060
[Guest]: And there were plenty of people who disagreed with it.

01:23:11.060 --> 01:23:13.380
[Guest]: And I think, in my opinion, they were right.

01:23:13.380 --> 01:23:16.660
[Guest]: I'm sure probably were others who felt differently.

01:23:16.660 --> 01:23:24.220
[Guest]: But once you normalize, and again, if I can just go to the Mukherjee's retort to Nehru

01:23:24.220 --> 01:23:30.500
[Guest]: really makes clear where he says, you know, you may be in power for this generation or

01:23:30.500 --> 01:23:35.460
[Guest]: for generations unborn, but supposing someone else comes into government, what is the precedent

01:23:35.460 --> 01:23:36.460
[Guest]: that you're laying down?

01:23:36.460 --> 01:23:42.260
[Guest]: And that's, I think, one of the most unfortunate consequences is that once you create a precedent

01:23:42.260 --> 01:23:48.420
[Guest]: and an avenue for something to be done, there's really nothing stopping someone else from

01:23:48.420 --> 01:23:53.740
[Guest]: utilizing the same mechanisms to the opposite effect.

01:23:53.740 --> 01:23:58.780
[Guest]: And that's kind of how, and Mukherjee has been proven true, I think.

01:23:58.780 --> 01:24:01.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I have three kind of observations here.

01:24:01.500 --> 01:24:06.580
[Amit Varma]: One is I had done an episode with Gyan Prakash on the emergency and the point he made there,

01:24:06.580 --> 01:24:11.020
[Amit Varma]: and you also quoted him in your book, is that, look, what Indira Gandhi did in 75 calling

01:24:11.020 --> 01:24:14.420
[Amit Varma]: the emergency was not unconstitutional or extraordinary.

01:24:14.420 --> 01:24:17.680
[Amit Varma]: It was delineated in the powers given to the state.

01:24:17.680 --> 01:24:20.900
[Amit Varma]: Those extreme powers were given to the state.

01:24:20.900 --> 01:24:25.820
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that's in the design of the state, which to a large extent remains.

01:24:25.820 --> 01:24:31.460
[Amit Varma]: The second thought that strikes me is that in this position that Nehru is taking in constitutional

01:24:31.460 --> 01:24:36.100
[Amit Varma]: morality versus democracy, and I agree with you that he took the wrong position.

01:24:36.100 --> 01:24:39.820
[Amit Varma]: And in this position that he is taking, you could argue that in the long run, he is laying

01:24:39.820 --> 01:24:45.580
[Amit Varma]: down the roots of a Hindu Rashtra, because if our society is such that the kind of dispensation

01:24:45.580 --> 01:24:50.420
[Amit Varma]: that is in power today will one day get into the government, if you follow Nehru's argument

01:24:50.420 --> 01:24:55.620
[Amit Varma]: to his logical end, then that means that these guys would be correct to change the constitution

01:24:55.620 --> 01:25:00.940
[Amit Varma]: to reflect what they feel is a popular mandate that they have got.

01:25:00.940 --> 01:25:05.940
[Amit Varma]: And many of the people from, you know, Nehru's party today would sort of perhaps not recognize

01:25:05.940 --> 01:25:06.940
[Amit Varma]: that.

01:25:06.940 --> 01:25:10.220
[Amit Varma]: But that's a logical end of Nehru's own kind of actions.

01:25:10.220 --> 01:25:14.540
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one common question that I often ask my guests, so much so that it's almost

01:25:14.540 --> 01:25:20.380
[Amit Varma]: become a cliche, and I'm sure you've heard it in past episodes is about this odd paradox

01:25:20.380 --> 01:25:25.020
[Amit Varma]: of our constitution, which is, and let's go to the original 1950 constitution and imagine

01:25:25.020 --> 01:25:30.780
[Amit Varma]: that the First Amendment isn't there yet, and which is of a relatively liberal constitution

01:25:30.780 --> 01:25:33.580
[Amit Varma]: being imposed on an illiberal society.

01:25:33.580 --> 01:25:39.300
[Amit Varma]: And you know, then how liberal can that imposition be, that a group of unelected elites, as it

01:25:39.300 --> 01:25:44.020
[Amit Varma]: were, are sitting and saying that these are the values that we should live by.

01:25:44.020 --> 01:25:47.580
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that, you know, I feel conflicted about, because those values, of

01:25:47.580 --> 01:25:49.460
[Amit Varma]: course, I agree with.

01:25:49.460 --> 01:25:54.140
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, I can't square that circle and say that, why should I, you know,

01:25:54.140 --> 01:25:58.180
[Amit Varma]: the core part of my value system is that I shall not impose my values on others.

01:25:58.180 --> 01:26:00.660
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how does one square that circle?

01:26:00.660 --> 01:26:02.780
[Guest]: What are your sort of thoughts on this?

01:26:02.780 --> 01:26:03.780
[Guest]: Interesting question.

01:26:03.780 --> 01:26:08.780
[Guest]: There is one very revealing quote, I'm not sure who said it in the Constituent Assembly,

01:26:08.780 --> 01:26:12.700
[Guest]: but someone said, you know, we were expecting the sounds of the veena and we got the sounds

01:26:12.700 --> 01:26:14.740
[Guest]: of an orchestra or something.

01:26:14.740 --> 01:26:15.740
[Guest]: It's something like that.

01:26:15.740 --> 01:26:22.120
[Guest]: Essentially, many people felt that the constitution wasn't rooted in a kind of, in the social

01:26:22.120 --> 01:26:27.020
[Guest]: milieu in which it was being born.

01:26:27.020 --> 01:26:34.860
[Guest]: And the one of, again, I kind of quote, I'm quoting Madhav Khosla here, because his most

01:26:34.860 --> 01:26:42.540
[Guest]: recent study of the constitution, the argument is that the constitution in itself is a kind

01:26:42.540 --> 01:26:44.380
[Guest]: of pedagogic document.

01:26:44.380 --> 01:26:51.100
[Guest]: So by practicing what the constitution is giving, you will be creating a kind of democratic

01:26:51.100 --> 01:26:57.620
[Guest]: citizen rather than there being a kind of popular upsurge, which results in the constitution.

01:26:57.620 --> 01:27:02.100
[Guest]: And it's an interesting, it's an interesting argument to make, because there is a sense

01:27:02.100 --> 01:27:04.020
[Guest]: that's what people thought.

01:27:04.020 --> 01:27:11.620
[Guest]: But equally it's, I mean, people are not very willing to be kind of educated in that way.

01:27:11.620 --> 01:27:18.620
[Guest]: And everyone kind of recognized that, and Ambedkar most prominently recognized that

01:27:18.620 --> 01:27:25.020
[Guest]: what was happening was that you were creating a kind of, you know, in his words, a democratic

01:27:25.020 --> 01:27:31.620
[Guest]: topsoil, topsoil based on the sort of subsoil of an undemocratic society.

01:27:31.620 --> 01:27:33.540
[Guest]: And it was an experiment.

01:27:33.540 --> 01:27:37.380
[Guest]: It was, you know, most constitutional scholars, you know, journalists, et cetera, everybody

01:27:37.380 --> 01:27:43.020
[Guest]: noted that it was a kind of brave and great experiment in democratic government.

01:27:43.020 --> 01:27:47.620
[Guest]: And that's one of the things that makes it so exceptional is the fact that it was a kind

01:27:47.620 --> 01:27:49.420
[Guest]: of leap of faith.

01:27:49.420 --> 01:27:58.340
[Guest]: But having committed themselves to it, the mistake that India's sort of early post-colonial

01:27:58.340 --> 01:28:06.340
[Guest]: elite made is the same that the British made when they first introduced provincial legislate,

01:28:06.340 --> 01:28:12.140
[Guest]: like popular legislatures in the provinces, is that once you introduce a kind of democratic

01:28:12.140 --> 01:28:19.820
[Guest]: system or a constitutional system, you have to be at some level willing to bear the consequences

01:28:19.820 --> 01:28:21.820
[Guest]: that accrue.

01:28:21.820 --> 01:28:26.220
[Guest]: And that was something that the Indian elite was unwilling to do.

01:28:26.220 --> 01:28:31.260
[Guest]: Now, we can make the case that there was, as Nehru tried to make, that there was a kind

01:28:31.260 --> 01:28:38.460
[Guest]: of grave threat to national security, to public order, and we can debate whether there was,

01:28:38.460 --> 01:28:46.780
[Guest]: but equally there are as many important figures who refuse to believe that such a thing existed,

01:28:46.780 --> 01:28:49.180
[Guest]: that there was such a grave threat.

01:28:49.180 --> 01:29:00.340
[Guest]: So I think squaring that kind of circle requires a certain broad-based commitment to the constitutional

01:29:00.340 --> 01:29:08.060
[Guest]: ideal that was, I think, not quite present even within the Congress party.

01:29:08.060 --> 01:29:15.300
[Guest]: And that's, I think, we're still kind of struggling to really square that circle because we've,

01:29:15.300 --> 01:29:21.100
[Guest]: in a way, uncorked a genie almost with the First Amendment.

01:29:21.100 --> 01:29:28.780
[Guest]: And obviously now it's been amended about 105 times, I think, possibly even more.

01:29:28.780 --> 01:29:36.660
[Guest]: And we're now at a point where without kind of going back to and redeveloping a sort of

01:29:36.660 --> 01:29:45.140
[Guest]: consensus on constitutional first principles, really, it's difficult to even contemplate

01:29:45.140 --> 01:29:50.340
[Guest]: squaring that circle because if you ask the two sides of the political divide, they have

01:29:50.340 --> 01:29:59.540
[Guest]: almost completely diametrically opposite readings of what the Constitution is and what it represents.

01:29:59.540 --> 01:30:03.980
[Guest]: And to square that is, I mean, it's quite a difficult proposition.

01:30:03.980 --> 01:30:06.940
[Amit Varma]: I mean, now, as you said, it's a done deal.

01:30:06.940 --> 01:30:08.500
[Amit Varma]: By the way, I mean, people don't realize this.

01:30:08.500 --> 01:30:12.620
[Amit Varma]: People often express shock and horror when they think of the BJP wanting to amend the

01:30:12.620 --> 01:30:13.620
[Amit Varma]: Constitution.

01:30:13.620 --> 01:30:16.460
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, as I mentioned earlier, there was an old cartoon about how it's not a book,

01:30:16.460 --> 01:30:17.980
[Amit Varma]: but a periodical.

01:30:17.980 --> 01:30:22.820
[Amit Varma]: And the economist Shruti Rajgopalan, who's a frequent guest on the show, had once given

01:30:22.820 --> 01:30:26.260
[Amit Varma]: a talk on YouTube, which I'll link to where she talks about all the different amendments

01:30:26.260 --> 01:30:28.260
[Amit Varma]: under Nehru to begin with.

01:30:28.260 --> 01:30:31.860
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, some people have this impression that, hey, the amendments and the messing

01:30:31.860 --> 01:30:35.100
[Amit Varma]: around started with Indira Gandhi and Nehru was a constitutionalist.

01:30:35.100 --> 01:30:40.020
[Amit Varma]: And that's just a rubbish as, you know, your book and subsequent events also show.

01:30:40.020 --> 01:30:44.260
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that I'm kind of struck by to sort of continue thinking aloud and be

01:30:44.260 --> 01:30:49.700
[Amit Varma]: on a tangent is that what we often have, what disturbs me today, especially about politics

01:30:49.700 --> 01:30:54.600
[Amit Varma]: is that politics has, and I imagine it was, you know, I would have thought it was less

01:30:54.600 --> 01:30:57.540
[Amit Varma]: so in Nehru's time, but, you know, who knows.

01:30:57.540 --> 01:31:02.060
[Amit Varma]: But what it has become is that it is tribal to the extent that people just care about

01:31:02.060 --> 01:31:06.180
[Amit Varma]: which tribe they are part of and not about principles per se.

01:31:06.180 --> 01:31:12.380
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you'll have people protesting about 153A and 295A when it's being used against

01:31:12.380 --> 01:31:16.940
[Amit Varma]: one of their own, but they're quite happy to, you know, see it used against somebody

01:31:16.940 --> 01:31:22.580
[Amit Varma]: else where, you know, how you judge a policy really comes down to which side you're on

01:31:22.580 --> 01:31:24.300
[Amit Varma]: and which side is carrying the policy out.

01:31:24.300 --> 01:31:28.620
[Amit Varma]: Like in these recent farm bills, for example, I was, you know, it's interesting how a lot

01:31:28.620 --> 01:31:33.380
[Amit Varma]: of what has been enacted in these farm bills was part of the Congress manifesto in 2019

01:31:33.380 --> 01:31:36.100
[Amit Varma]: and they're protesting those very same things.

01:31:36.100 --> 01:31:40.540
[Amit Varma]: And therefore it's become a politics of just tribalism of you pick your side and you go

01:31:40.540 --> 01:31:42.700
[Amit Varma]: with it and not principles per se.

01:31:42.700 --> 01:31:48.460
[Amit Varma]: And therefore it strikes me that no view that sort of really takes constitutionalism seriously

01:31:48.460 --> 01:31:53.680
[Amit Varma]: is going to, you know, get any kind of traction because people don't care about principles

01:31:53.680 --> 01:31:54.680
[Amit Varma]: even today.

01:31:54.680 --> 01:31:59.300
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's just about which side you're on and then you say whatever, but in practice

01:31:59.300 --> 01:32:00.300
[Amit Varma]: you don't.

01:32:00.300 --> 01:32:03.780
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is a bit of an aside from me, I'm just thinking aloud, but what are sort

01:32:03.780 --> 01:32:09.380
[Amit Varma]: of your thoughts on this and going back to that time, was there a sense of it then because

01:32:09.380 --> 01:32:14.260
[Amit Varma]: the parties weren't so hardened and, you know, different things from each other at the time?

01:32:14.260 --> 01:32:15.260
[Guest]: Well, you're right.

01:32:15.260 --> 01:32:18.620
[Guest]: They don't really think in terms of those sort of principles, but as the book bears

01:32:18.620 --> 01:32:25.900
[Guest]: out they didn't seem to be thinking that strongly about principles, you know, in 1951 either.

01:32:25.900 --> 01:32:32.140
[Guest]: And I think the way to really, and principles are, I feel like, quite a sort of top-down

01:32:32.140 --> 01:32:33.140
[Guest]: manner.

01:32:33.140 --> 01:32:38.420
[Guest]: The leaders have to demonstrate a commitment to constitutional morality if they expect

01:32:38.420 --> 01:32:40.820
[Guest]: it to kind of percolate downwards.

01:32:40.820 --> 01:32:44.780
[Guest]: And they just didn't, right from the word go.

01:32:44.780 --> 01:32:49.900
[Guest]: Again, in the context of the book you have, you know, at one point Nehru buried someone

01:32:49.900 --> 01:32:50.900
[Guest]: like K.V.

01:32:50.900 --> 01:32:55.340
[Guest]: Kamath, who, you know, intervenes at some point and he asked him not to quote things

01:32:55.340 --> 01:33:02.260
[Guest]: which are relevant at the time of the French Revolution and, you know, the American Revolution.

01:33:02.260 --> 01:33:08.380
[Guest]: So that was, I think, a pivotal moment in demonstrating that constitutional principles

01:33:08.380 --> 01:33:16.300
[Guest]: could be undone in pursuit of an obviously political agenda.

01:33:16.300 --> 01:33:20.860
[Guest]: In today's day and age, again, because it's something, I think, each precedent kind of

01:33:20.860 --> 01:33:23.420
[Guest]: builds on what comes before.

01:33:23.420 --> 01:33:26.180
[Guest]: Things get normalized very, very quickly.

01:33:26.180 --> 01:33:34.260
[Guest]: Things that we, you know, laws such as, you know, 153A and 295A, as you mentioned, which

01:33:34.260 --> 01:33:36.660
[Guest]: we now take for granted as existing in the books.

01:33:36.660 --> 01:33:42.300
[Guest]: We often don't remember that, you know, they were, as intended by the Constituent Assembly,

01:33:42.300 --> 01:33:46.140
[Guest]: these were not supposed to be allowed to continue.

01:33:46.140 --> 01:33:51.420
[Guest]: So it's, even back then, the situation was not drastically different.

01:33:51.420 --> 01:33:57.900
[Guest]: I mean, it was different to the extent that there was a sense of idealism and a particular

01:33:57.900 --> 01:34:01.180
[Guest]: dispensation was in power and remained in power for a very long time.

01:34:01.180 --> 01:34:05.780
[Guest]: But I don't think it was very different in terms of attitudes or in terms of commitment

01:34:05.780 --> 01:34:11.340
[Guest]: to constitutional principles, because if the constitution itself is malleable and changeable,

01:34:11.340 --> 01:34:17.300
[Guest]: it can't really, it obviously can't lead to a kind of enduring legal norms if those norms

01:34:17.300 --> 01:34:19.420
[Guest]: themselves are subject to frequent change.

01:34:19.420 --> 01:34:22.420
[Guest]: I think that's kind of what I would say to that, really.

01:34:22.420 --> 01:34:23.420
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:34:23.420 --> 01:34:27.860
[Amit Varma]: And I'll again sort of quote from your book, because we are speaking about 153A and 295A

01:34:27.860 --> 01:34:30.340
[Amit Varma]: and there's also 124A, which is sedition.

01:34:30.340 --> 01:34:35.300
[Amit Varma]: And you've pointed out in your book quote, far from being a simple remnant of colonialism,

01:34:35.300 --> 01:34:39.180
[Amit Varma]: sedition is an outcome of the first amendment of the constitution and the narrow government's

01:34:39.180 --> 01:34:45.700
[Amit Varma]: desire to clamp down on critical voices unencumbered by constitutional obligations, a truly deliberate

01:34:45.700 --> 01:34:51.500
[Amit Varma]: and strategic assault on the constitution and fundamental rights, stop quote.

01:34:51.500 --> 01:35:00.020
[Amit Varma]: And so just clarify this for me, that my impression about these laws, 124A, 153A, 295A was that

01:35:00.020 --> 01:35:05.060
[Amit Varma]: any of the laws that are in the Indian penal code can be challenged if they are unconstitutional

01:35:05.060 --> 01:35:06.340
[Amit Varma]: and struck down.

01:35:06.340 --> 01:35:09.620
[Amit Varma]: And that is what would have happened in the case of these laws in the normal course of

01:35:09.620 --> 01:35:10.620
[Amit Varma]: things.

01:35:10.620 --> 01:35:15.860
[Amit Varma]: But the first amendment added those other sort of caveats to free speech.

01:35:15.860 --> 01:35:19.020
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, these laws kind of remained in the book.

01:35:19.020 --> 01:35:23.900
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you're saying it's a responsibility of the first amendment and Nehru therefore,

01:35:23.900 --> 01:35:26.220
[Amit Varma]: that we have the law of sedition with us.

01:35:26.220 --> 01:35:27.220
[Amit Varma]: Is that correct?

01:35:27.220 --> 01:35:28.220
[Guest]: That's true.

01:35:28.220 --> 01:35:31.460
[Guest]: And not only the idea that they would have been struck down, in fact, they were struck

01:35:31.460 --> 01:35:36.340
[Guest]: down most prominently in the case of Master Tara Singh in Punjab, when he was charged

01:35:36.340 --> 01:35:41.460
[Guest]: with sedition and the court held sedition to be unconstitutional.

01:35:41.460 --> 01:35:47.460
[Guest]: And sedition was, I mean, it was very clear that it was unconstitutional.

01:35:47.460 --> 01:35:50.700
[Guest]: It was very clear that the Constituent Assembly didn't want it and they didn't want it especially

01:35:50.700 --> 01:35:58.340
[Guest]: because of its association with repression in the British period, because most of the

01:35:58.340 --> 01:36:02.580
[Guest]: Congress stalwarts had been charged with sedition and jailed.

01:36:02.580 --> 01:36:08.580
[Guest]: And it's a point they make repeatedly during the debate that this was an act that was used

01:36:08.580 --> 01:36:13.660
[Guest]: against patriots and nationalists under British rule.

01:36:13.660 --> 01:36:17.980
[Guest]: And we can't be, I mean, we shouldn't, really shouldn't be bringing it back on the books.

01:36:17.980 --> 01:36:23.700
[Guest]: But it was, yes, you're absolutely right, they were unconstitutional.

01:36:23.700 --> 01:36:28.260
[Guest]: And they were brought back, they were brought back for a particular end.

01:36:28.260 --> 01:36:35.740
[Guest]: You might say that, well, the ends that Nehru thought were benevolent or somehow justified,

01:36:35.740 --> 01:36:38.260
[Guest]: but they were brought back.

01:36:38.260 --> 01:36:44.740
[Guest]: I mean, there was, it's perhaps hard to imagine now, but there was a period in time where

01:36:44.740 --> 01:36:47.980
[Guest]: these sections of the Indian Penal Code were unconstitutional.

01:36:47.980 --> 01:36:53.620
[Guest]: You could not be charged with sedition in the year 1950 because it was an unconstitutional

01:36:53.620 --> 01:36:57.140
[Guest]: part of the IPC.

01:36:57.140 --> 01:37:02.340
[Guest]: And I mean, I don't think Nehru alone is responsible, because obviously, there's been plenty of

01:37:02.340 --> 01:37:09.460
[Guest]: opportunities to repeal it or replace it with something else, and they haven't been taken.

01:37:09.460 --> 01:37:16.260
[Guest]: But Nehru is responsible to the extent that he creates a set of legal tools, which he

01:37:16.260 --> 01:37:22.500
[Guest]: describes kind of quite ironically as something that he wants to leave for the succeeding

01:37:22.500 --> 01:37:24.500
[Guest]: generations.

01:37:24.500 --> 01:37:26.780
[Guest]: And well, here we are.

01:37:26.780 --> 01:37:28.180
[Amit Varma]: And here we are indeed.

01:37:28.180 --> 01:37:30.740
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, your book goes like a bullet.

01:37:30.740 --> 01:37:32.780
[Amit Varma]: This episode has been floating like a feather.

01:37:32.780 --> 01:37:36.220
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of get back to the narrative and get back to the third fault line.

01:37:36.220 --> 01:37:40.860
[Amit Varma]: We've already spoken about the zamindari reforms, which the fundamental rights came in the way

01:37:40.860 --> 01:37:43.700
[Amit Varma]: of the right to property and the right to equality.

01:37:43.700 --> 01:37:49.020
[Amit Varma]: We've spoken about how he wanted to control the press and the right to free speech came

01:37:49.020 --> 01:37:50.460
[Amit Varma]: in the way of that.

01:37:50.460 --> 01:37:52.140
[Amit Varma]: And what's the third fault line?

01:37:52.140 --> 01:37:58.460
[Guest]: So the third fault line is reservations, and that, again, is something that begins in Madras.

01:37:58.460 --> 01:38:05.020
[Guest]: Because I mean, Madras had been, the erstwhile Madras province, had been a kind of crucible

01:38:05.020 --> 01:38:11.220
[Guest]: for social justice politics with the creation of the Justice Party, the kind of appearance

01:38:11.220 --> 01:38:21.540
[Guest]: of Periyar, and the Justice Party had kind of enacted all of these sort of mechanisms,

01:38:21.540 --> 01:38:25.540
[Guest]: social justice mechanisms, amongst which was something called the communal general order,

01:38:25.540 --> 01:38:32.140
[Guest]: which allocated government employment and access to educational and government educational

01:38:32.140 --> 01:38:37.060
[Guest]: institutes in a particular ratio amongst communities.

01:38:37.060 --> 01:38:44.460
[Guest]: It was quite a peculiar instrument because what it did was it kind of allocated seats,

01:38:44.460 --> 01:38:47.100
[Guest]: for example, in a particular ratio.

01:38:47.100 --> 01:38:53.860
[Guest]: And so if the ratio was, I think it was something like every 14 seats, five could be Brahmins

01:38:53.860 --> 01:38:56.740
[Guest]: and three would be something else.

01:38:56.740 --> 01:39:05.580
[Guest]: So there would only be five Brahmins and it didn't matter if it was, I mean, it was almost

01:39:05.580 --> 01:39:13.060
[Guest]: a kind of ironclad quota, a kind of government-sanctioned distribution almost in a particular ratio

01:39:13.060 --> 01:39:18.300
[Guest]: rather than the way we understand reservations now.

01:39:18.300 --> 01:39:22.140
[Guest]: And so if only seven Brahmins were allowed, then the number of Brahmins could not be greater

01:39:22.140 --> 01:39:27.140
[Guest]: than seven, for example, or if the number of Harijans that were allowed was six out

01:39:27.140 --> 01:39:30.540
[Guest]: of 14, then they could not be six out of 14.

01:39:30.540 --> 01:39:37.640
[Guest]: It's not as if someone could get greater marks and go into another quota.

01:39:37.640 --> 01:39:45.400
[Guest]: So everyone was really subject to this system of quotas and that was challenged by a woman

01:39:45.400 --> 01:39:52.420
[Guest]: named Champakam Durairajan who had interestingly not even actually applied for admission but

01:39:52.420 --> 01:40:00.060
[Guest]: wanted to apply for admission and had been effectively told that her grades wouldn't

01:40:00.060 --> 01:40:03.500
[Guest]: allow her in through the Brahmin quota.

01:40:03.500 --> 01:40:08.900
[Guest]: And obviously there were other people with lower grades who would get in from their own

01:40:08.900 --> 01:40:10.740
[Guest]: community-based quotas.

01:40:10.740 --> 01:40:16.340
[Guest]: And so she kind of files a petition in the High Court in Madras.

01:40:16.340 --> 01:40:23.600
[Guest]: And the High Court in Madras, it arouses quite a lot of passion because it's a kind of great,

01:40:23.600 --> 01:40:29.540
[Guest]: it's a question that touches upon a lot of lives and you have a lot of protests, etc.

01:40:29.540 --> 01:40:35.580
[Guest]: The court holds a kind of interesting position.

01:40:35.580 --> 01:40:45.220
[Guest]: So what the court effectively does is the court finds the communal general order unconstitutional

01:40:45.220 --> 01:40:54.140
[Guest]: but what it also notes is that considerations of caste and community were not only not allowed,

01:40:54.140 --> 01:40:59.820
[Guest]: they were expressly taboo and that's the kind of language, it's quite stern, the language

01:40:59.820 --> 01:41:03.180
[Guest]: the court uses.

01:41:03.180 --> 01:41:07.840
[Guest]: And they keep saying basically that the right to equality and the right to freedom from

01:41:07.840 --> 01:41:13.500
[Guest]: discrimination will effectively become empty bubbles if the executive orders like the communal

01:41:13.500 --> 01:41:19.660
[Guest]: general order are allowed to be implemented or allowed to continue.

01:41:19.660 --> 01:41:27.100
[Guest]: So basically, again, an interesting aside, the petitioners were represented by the noted

01:41:27.100 --> 01:41:31.180
[Guest]: lawyer Alladi Krishnaswami Iyer, who again had been one of the key architects of the

01:41:31.180 --> 01:41:38.700
[Guest]: constitution and also someone who advised the government on the amendment, which nullified

01:41:38.700 --> 01:41:46.180
[Guest]: a court order that he himself had won, which I still find the kind of intellectual somersaults

01:41:46.180 --> 01:41:49.140
[Guest]: that many of these people perform to be quite interesting.

01:41:49.140 --> 01:41:55.260
[Guest]: What the Madras government basically submits in court, it doesn't, it never really argued

01:41:55.260 --> 01:41:57.940
[Guest]: that the quotas didn't amount to discrimination.

01:41:57.940 --> 01:42:03.460
[Guest]: What it said was as a result of applying the ratio prescribed by the communal geo, 77 Brahmins,

01:42:03.460 --> 01:42:10.460
[Guest]: 224 non-Brahmins, 51 Christians, 26 Muslims and 26 Harijans had been selected for admission

01:42:10.460 --> 01:42:11.660
[Guest]: to engineering colleges.

01:42:11.660 --> 01:42:15.540
[Guest]: If caste and community considerations had been ignored, the numbers would have been

01:42:15.540 --> 01:42:21.460
[Guest]: 249 Brahmins, 112 non-Brahmins, 22 Christians, 3 Muslims and 0 Harijans.

01:42:21.460 --> 01:42:28.940
[Guest]: So to avoid this sort of system and to fulfil what they saw as a responsibility under the

01:42:28.940 --> 01:42:35.140
[Guest]: director principles of state policy, they had created this order.

01:42:35.140 --> 01:42:41.940
[Guest]: But again, the court, and if you don't mind, I'll just quote from the court order again,

01:42:41.940 --> 01:42:46.220
[Guest]: they say the communal geo denies equal treatment for all citizens under like circumstances

01:42:46.220 --> 01:42:51.060
[Guest]: and conditions, both in the privileges conferred and the disabilities imposed.

01:42:51.060 --> 01:42:55.860
[Guest]: It shuts out students having high qualifications solely on the grounds of their caste or religion

01:42:55.860 --> 01:42:59.780
[Guest]: and lets in others with inferior qualifications on the same ground.

01:42:59.780 --> 01:43:03.340
[Guest]: As the articles of the constitution stand at present, it is difficult to see how the

01:43:03.340 --> 01:43:07.900
[Guest]: state can make discrimination between applicant and applicant on the grounds of religion or

01:43:07.900 --> 01:43:12.220
[Guest]: caste and restrict the number of seats that could be secured by applicants of any particular

01:43:12.220 --> 01:43:16.460
[Guest]: religion or caste, or prescribe different qualifications to applicants of different

01:43:16.460 --> 01:43:21.940
[Guest]: religions or castes to the advantage of some and the disadvantage of others.

01:43:21.940 --> 01:43:26.160
[Guest]: Does social justice or the welfare of the state require a suppression of the integrity

01:43:26.160 --> 01:43:31.380
[Guest]: and freedom of the individual personality of the citizen by reason of his belonging

01:43:31.380 --> 01:43:33.540
[Guest]: to a particular caste?

01:43:33.540 --> 01:43:40.540
[Guest]: And so the court is quite strict and it, I mean, even when they end the judgment, and

01:43:40.540 --> 01:43:45.580
[Guest]: I quote again, if the person in charge for the time being of a state elected no doubt

01:43:45.580 --> 01:43:50.540
[Guest]: by a majority of voters at the polls were free to enforce their own notions of social

01:43:50.540 --> 01:43:55.780
[Guest]: and economic justice unfettered by constitutional restraints, there is a possibility of serious

01:43:55.780 --> 01:44:00.340
[Guest]: and undeserved hardship and injury to large classes of citizens.

01:44:00.340 --> 01:44:05.380
[Guest]: Suppression of a guaranteed right in article 15.1 of the constitution would be worthless

01:44:05.380 --> 01:44:09.980
[Guest]: if the government could disregard or nullify it by executive acts like the communal general

01:44:09.980 --> 01:44:11.100
[Guest]: order.

01:44:11.100 --> 01:44:17.860
[Guest]: And so the court is, I mean, effectively what it is saying is that any form of consideration

01:44:17.860 --> 01:44:25.260
[Guest]: of caste or community or religion into questions about employment or education is expressly

01:44:25.260 --> 01:44:34.460
[Guest]: taboo and what's, I mean, what's basically prevented by the sort of chapter on fundamental

01:44:34.460 --> 01:44:41.100
[Guest]: rights cannot then be enabled through the back door by the chapter on directive principles.

01:44:41.100 --> 01:44:46.660
[Guest]: And again, what the courts delineate is a kind of bastion of, not really a bastion,

01:44:46.660 --> 01:44:53.180
[Guest]: but a kind of bedrock of constitutional thought that fundamental rights effectively trump

01:44:53.180 --> 01:44:56.480
[Guest]: the directive principles of state policy.

01:44:56.480 --> 01:45:01.780
[Guest]: And this is something that the Nehru government doesn't completely agree with.

01:45:01.780 --> 01:45:06.940
[Guest]: And it's interesting to read Nehru's responses to this because the directive principles of

01:45:06.940 --> 01:45:13.540
[Guest]: state policy are kind of a hodgepodge of all sorts of things, including, you know, some

01:45:13.540 --> 01:45:17.700
[Guest]: concern education, some concern backward class welfare, but equally there are others which

01:45:17.700 --> 01:45:23.420
[Guest]: can concern animal husbandry and protection of cows.

01:45:23.420 --> 01:45:29.380
[Guest]: And if that, again, as something that we discussed earlier on, if, for example, someone was to

01:45:29.380 --> 01:45:35.340
[Guest]: take Nehru's position with respect to the article in the directive principles with regard

01:45:35.340 --> 01:45:42.100
[Guest]: to protection of cows, what could then, you know, what it could lead to something, sort

01:45:42.100 --> 01:45:48.260
[Guest]: of consequences that we would today be, you know, be right to question.

01:45:48.260 --> 01:45:55.060
[Guest]: So again, anyway, this, this judgment comes in, it really shocks the Madras government

01:45:55.060 --> 01:46:01.540
[Guest]: because the Madras government is, this has been an article of faith in Madras.

01:46:01.540 --> 01:46:06.980
[Guest]: Initially, of course, the Congress had opposed it when it was the Justice Party doing it,

01:46:06.980 --> 01:46:13.820
[Guest]: but this kind of social justice politics had acquired deep roots in Madras and the Congress

01:46:13.820 --> 01:46:15.940
[Guest]: government had continued with those policies.

01:46:15.940 --> 01:46:19.660
[Guest]: It was committed to reservations as an ideal.

01:46:19.660 --> 01:46:25.340
[Guest]: There was crucially, again, the question of an election coming up.

01:46:25.340 --> 01:46:31.460
[Guest]: The Madras Congress was right in its fears that there was a possibility that it would

01:46:31.460 --> 01:46:32.780
[Guest]: lose.

01:46:32.780 --> 01:46:39.260
[Guest]: And so they were quite, I mean, this is something that caused a lot of agitation within Madras.

01:46:39.260 --> 01:46:45.540
[Guest]: Interestingly, this is a question out of like the three sort of fault lines that you mentioned.

01:46:45.540 --> 01:46:49.260
[Guest]: This is the one that Nehru was the least invested in.

01:46:49.260 --> 01:46:56.660
[Guest]: So even though there was plenty of pressure from Madras to completely override Article

01:46:56.660 --> 01:47:04.220
[Guest]: 15, and also I think Article 29, which prohibited discrimination in the matter of admissions

01:47:04.220 --> 01:47:12.820
[Guest]: to educational institutions receiving state aid, this was something that Nehru cast, was

01:47:12.820 --> 01:47:19.420
[Guest]: something specifically that Nehru was kind of loathe to address, I would say.

01:47:19.420 --> 01:47:25.340
[Guest]: And so it's unlike the other two in which his mind is quite firmly made up, this third

01:47:25.340 --> 01:47:28.220
[Guest]: fault line takes a while to kind of build.

01:47:28.220 --> 01:47:33.780
[Guest]: There's pressure from Madras, the chief minister comes to Delhi to speak to him, ministerial

01:47:33.780 --> 01:47:37.260
[Guest]: delegations from Delhi come to speak to him.

01:47:37.260 --> 01:47:47.260
[Guest]: The initially Nehru's advice is for them to rewrite the communal general order to be in

01:47:47.260 --> 01:47:51.620
[Guest]: conformity with the constitution.

01:47:51.620 --> 01:47:58.740
[Guest]: But of course eventually he comes around and I think, and the literature on this is slightly

01:47:58.740 --> 01:48:10.580
[Guest]: hazy because it's something that is both in a way there is a kind of consensus that the

01:48:10.580 --> 01:48:17.700
[Guest]: state should be committed to the welfare of backward classes of citizens, and in a way

01:48:17.700 --> 01:48:26.700
[Guest]: there's no real clarity as to what it implies, because there had been no, unlike the question

01:48:26.700 --> 01:48:33.060
[Guest]: of the schedule cast, which had been tackled in the constitution, this was still a sort

01:48:33.060 --> 01:48:34.060
[Guest]: of work in progress.

01:48:34.060 --> 01:48:41.060
[Guest]: Nobody really knew what it was going to entail or who was going to kind of be classified

01:48:41.060 --> 01:48:47.200
[Guest]: as a backward class, what criteria would be used.

01:48:47.200 --> 01:48:53.500
[Guest]: So some of the opposition that came, of course, to the amendment did note that there was no

01:48:53.500 --> 01:49:04.220
[Guest]: clarity on this, there was no real way to tell what the consequences would be, and no

01:49:04.220 --> 01:49:08.860
[Guest]: way to really tell whether it would be misused by the state, although many suspected that

01:49:08.860 --> 01:49:11.540
[Guest]: it would be misused by the state.

01:49:11.540 --> 01:49:19.300
[Guest]: So this is, I think, the kind of strand in which Nehru was less the driving force and

01:49:19.300 --> 01:49:27.620
[Guest]: more the kind of, I think his role was more or less, he wasn't against it, but it was

01:49:27.620 --> 01:49:31.040
[Guest]: not something that he was strongly concerned with.

01:49:31.040 --> 01:49:36.980
[Guest]: So I think just the fact that the three things kind of came together sort of provided him

01:49:36.980 --> 01:49:44.560
[Guest]: with an opportunity to create the constitutional architecture for something that they might

01:49:44.560 --> 01:49:47.000
[Guest]: want to do in the future.

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:55.800
[Guest]: And just as a sort of last point, this is something that's not very clear in their correspondence,

01:49:55.800 --> 01:50:03.600
[Guest]: but I would suspect that it was one of the sort of ways where how someone like Ambedkar

01:50:03.600 --> 01:50:11.440
[Guest]: was brought to agree with the whole sort of broad contours of the amendment, because we

01:50:11.440 --> 01:50:20.600
[Guest]: know that Ambedkar was not quite in agreement with the strand of it that targeted free speech,

01:50:20.600 --> 01:50:22.160
[Guest]: for example.

01:50:22.160 --> 01:50:31.200
[Guest]: And so I think it might also have been a way of sort of neutralizing dissent by bringing

01:50:31.200 --> 01:50:35.640
[Guest]: in several elements into one package, really.

01:50:35.640 --> 01:50:42.400
[Amit Varma]: So let me try to, you know, parse and put in simple terms what this particular judgment

01:50:42.400 --> 01:50:45.320
[Amit Varma]: would have meant and what the court's point of view would be, and you can tell me if I'm

01:50:45.320 --> 01:50:50.640
[Amit Varma]: summarizing it correctly, is that the court basically referred to the fundamental right

01:50:50.640 --> 01:50:54.700
[Amit Varma]: of equality and said that, look, the state has to treat everyone equally.

01:50:54.700 --> 01:50:59.120
[Amit Varma]: That means the state cannot discriminate on the basis of caste and, hey, these reservations

01:50:59.120 --> 01:51:02.120
[Amit Varma]: are in this discrimination on the basis of caste.

01:51:02.120 --> 01:51:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Now you might justify it in this instance saying this is my lofty goal and the, you

01:51:07.000 --> 01:51:08.800
[Amit Varma]: know, this is how this will let me get there.

01:51:08.800 --> 01:51:10.240
[Amit Varma]: And that is an entirely separate argument.

01:51:10.240 --> 01:51:15.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, today, of course, reservations are conflated with caring about caste.

01:51:15.080 --> 01:51:19.760
[Amit Varma]: So you, you know, it's deeply politically incorrect to make an argument that, you know,

01:51:19.760 --> 01:51:23.400
[Amit Varma]: there are better ways to get rid of caste and reservations might actually be a top down

01:51:23.400 --> 01:51:27.520
[Amit Varma]: thing that make them worse or can be misused, but leave that aside.

01:51:27.520 --> 01:51:32.120
[Amit Varma]: Even if it is a tool that would work, the point that they're making is that once you

01:51:32.120 --> 01:51:38.400
[Amit Varma]: give in to the temptation of infringing this fundamental right of equality for whatever

01:51:38.400 --> 01:51:44.000
[Amit Varma]: reason, then what is to stop a popular government in the future from also infringing it for

01:51:44.000 --> 01:51:47.820
[Amit Varma]: some reason of their own in some other way that they deem fit.

01:51:47.820 --> 01:51:53.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it is better that we hold it as sacrosanct and just stick to it.

01:51:53.480 --> 01:51:54.680
[Guest]: Would that be a correct summation?

01:51:54.680 --> 01:51:57.220
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that was more or less the court's reasoning.

01:51:57.220 --> 01:52:04.480
[Guest]: They were quite certain and they said quite clearly that if any government elected by

01:52:04.480 --> 01:52:10.680
[Guest]: a majority of the voters were allowed to have, you know, put their own considerations, express

01:52:10.680 --> 01:52:16.080
[Guest]: their own considerations through these sort of executive acts, then the entire, I mean,

01:52:16.080 --> 01:52:20.560
[Guest]: Article 15 of the Constitution would effectively become worthless.

01:52:20.560 --> 01:52:22.760
[Guest]: And the court, those are the court's words.

01:52:22.760 --> 01:52:27.560
[Guest]: So that's, yeah, that's a correct summation of the position.

01:52:27.560 --> 01:52:33.200
[Guest]: Interestingly, one of the sort of questions that comes up is how do you define social

01:52:33.200 --> 01:52:34.400
[Guest]: and educational backwardness?

01:52:34.400 --> 01:52:37.540
[Guest]: Are the two, you know, synonymous?

01:52:37.540 --> 01:52:43.100
[Guest]: And how much of a consideration is cast and how much of a consideration are the questions?

01:52:43.100 --> 01:52:50.640
[Guest]: And one of the key points of the amendment is that it leaves out any mention of economic

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:51.640
[Guest]: circumstances.

01:52:51.640 --> 01:52:58.640
[Guest]: The only way, what it effectively did was the only way in which such backwardness could

01:52:58.640 --> 01:53:01.780
[Guest]: be judged was on the basis of cost.

01:53:01.780 --> 01:53:06.340
[Guest]: So economic considerations were expressly disallowed.

01:53:06.340 --> 01:53:12.180
[Guest]: And so that in itself has led to the kind of, it's, that debate in itself carries on

01:53:12.180 --> 01:53:18.060
[Guest]: now in questions or in issues about, like, for example, the idea of the creamy layer

01:53:18.060 --> 01:53:23.620
[Guest]: that comes up every time a question about reservations reaches the courts about how

01:53:23.620 --> 01:53:32.420
[Guest]: do you exclude people who are supposedly socially backward but economically well-to-do.

01:53:32.420 --> 01:53:39.300
[Guest]: And many of these debates go, again, go back to this kind of, this moment in time.

01:53:39.300 --> 01:53:44.980
[Guest]: And so, again, on the question of Article 15, when the amendment was discussed within

01:53:44.980 --> 01:53:52.980
[Guest]: the cabinet, there's a rare sort of consensus on what should be done.

01:53:52.980 --> 01:53:58.140
[Guest]: Because from Madras, the idea is that there should be alteration of Article 15, but also

01:53:58.140 --> 01:54:06.260
[Guest]: Article 29, which had prevented discrimination in the matter of admissions to educational

01:54:06.260 --> 01:54:07.940
[Guest]: institutes.

01:54:07.940 --> 01:54:12.060
[Guest]: And they basically wanted an amendment to the effect stating that nothing in either

01:54:12.060 --> 01:54:17.100
[Guest]: Article 15 or Article 29 too would prevent special provisions for the educational, economic

01:54:17.100 --> 01:54:20.380
[Guest]: and social advancement of the backward classes.

01:54:20.380 --> 01:54:26.500
[Guest]: And the cabinet, I think most were of the belief, or at least that's what was expressed,

01:54:26.500 --> 01:54:32.580
[Guest]: that there was, you know, this could not be misused for any class discrimination that

01:54:32.580 --> 01:54:36.380
[Guest]: was against the spirit of the Constitution.

01:54:36.380 --> 01:54:42.500
[Guest]: There was, I think, broad-based consensus that the spirit of the Constitution implied

01:54:42.500 --> 01:54:48.700
[Guest]: that measures were taken for social justice, measures were taken for kind of the advancement

01:54:48.700 --> 01:54:51.380
[Guest]: of backward classes.

01:54:51.380 --> 01:54:56.900
[Guest]: But again, if I, I'm just going to quote directly from my book, in a new twist, the cabinet

01:54:56.900 --> 01:55:01.380
[Guest]: also recommended that all references to economic and economically be dropped and the language

01:55:01.380 --> 01:55:04.900
[Guest]: be limited to socially and educationally backward classes.

01:55:04.900 --> 01:55:08.180
[Guest]: Through this slate of hand, the cabinet sought to achieve two objectives.

01:55:08.180 --> 01:55:13.380
[Guest]: First, it would remove any prospect of economic criteria coming in the way of calculating

01:55:13.380 --> 01:55:18.380
[Guest]: the backwardness of a class based on their social and educational standing.

01:55:18.380 --> 01:55:23.220
[Guest]: Second, it would preempt and negate any demands for special provisions or reservations for

01:55:23.220 --> 01:55:27.820
[Guest]: those who could be termed economically backward without the corresponding status of social

01:55:27.820 --> 01:55:29.900
[Guest]: or educational backwardness.

01:55:29.900 --> 01:55:37.260
[Guest]: So basically, they wanted power to legislate for reservations, but equally they wanted

01:55:37.260 --> 01:55:45.300
[Guest]: to prevent a kind of open-ended, almost race to, you know, race to the bottom.

01:55:45.300 --> 01:55:50.700
[Guest]: Because as, again, as K. V. Kamath, you know, quite pointedly intervenes in the debate and

01:55:50.700 --> 01:55:58.900
[Guest]: he says on the question of backwardness, well, 90% of the country is backward and there is

01:55:58.900 --> 01:56:06.500
[Guest]: no way of, you know, really differentiating who's educationally and socially backward

01:56:06.500 --> 01:56:10.500
[Guest]: through the use of the, you know, lens of caste and community.

01:56:10.500 --> 01:56:14.100
[Guest]: But of course, I mean, that was not a popular position.

01:56:14.100 --> 01:56:21.780
[Guest]: And so the exclusion of economic backwardness from the kind of ambit of India's reservation

01:56:21.780 --> 01:56:27.740
[Guest]: policy was, is again something that can be traced back to the First Amendment.

01:56:27.740 --> 01:56:34.140
[Guest]: And I think, again, the cabinet and many of the parliamentarians were not quite certain

01:56:34.140 --> 01:56:39.100
[Guest]: as to how the process or the policy of reservations was going to be developed, because it was

01:56:39.100 --> 01:56:44.940
[Guest]: something that had yet to really be, you know, finalized.

01:56:44.940 --> 01:56:49.220
[Guest]: I think the first Backward Class Commission was appointed much after this.

01:56:49.220 --> 01:56:55.580
[Guest]: So I think today, many of the questions that we would consider today, questions about like

01:56:55.580 --> 01:57:01.260
[Guest]: recent before the 29 elections, of course, the government announced a kind of reservation

01:57:01.260 --> 01:57:04.340
[Guest]: policy for economically weaker sections.

01:57:04.340 --> 01:57:08.580
[Guest]: And of course, the question of the creamy layer within the backward classes keeps cropping

01:57:08.580 --> 01:57:09.580
[Guest]: up.

01:57:09.580 --> 01:57:12.660
[Guest]: And again, that's a question that goes back to the First Amendment.

01:57:12.660 --> 01:57:18.020
[Guest]: And I think that's, it's one of the most interesting sort of fault line of the three.

01:57:18.020 --> 01:57:22.940
[Guest]: It's probably possibly the most interesting, because at the time, it also seems to be the

01:57:22.940 --> 01:57:24.380
[Guest]: least important.

01:57:24.380 --> 01:57:26.940
[Guest]: The least amount of attention is paid to it.

01:57:26.940 --> 01:57:30.540
[Amit Varma]: Except in the south where Periyar railed against the judgment in rallies, and the Times of

01:57:30.540 --> 01:57:34.900
[Amit Varma]: India, you know, wrote about quote, crusaders for a separate Dravidistan are once again

01:57:34.900 --> 01:57:35.900
[Amit Varma]: on the march.

01:57:35.900 --> 01:57:36.900
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:57:36.900 --> 01:57:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And I imagine this would also have sort of put pressure on Nehru that you know, the center

01:57:41.000 --> 01:57:45.780
[Amit Varma]: must hold and these political imperatives also matter along with all the factors you

01:57:45.780 --> 01:57:51.340
[Amit Varma]: mentioned before, such as, you know, maybe keeping Ambedkar enthusiastic was part of

01:57:51.340 --> 01:57:52.340
[Amit Varma]: the mix.

01:57:52.340 --> 01:57:56.820
[Amit Varma]: So now that you know, all these three fault lines have come together, and you've repeatedly

01:57:56.820 --> 01:58:01.940
[Amit Varma]: quoted Nehru at different parts of the book, basically shitting on the constitution saying

01:58:01.940 --> 01:58:07.300
[Amit Varma]: that, hey, we need to kind of, you know, if the constitution isn't going along with us,

01:58:07.300 --> 01:58:11.860
[Amit Varma]: and we must get a, you know, change the constitution, and you sum it up very well here.

01:58:11.860 --> 01:58:18.300
[Amit Varma]: So I'll quickly quote this book where you write at the time of the, you know, just before

01:58:18.300 --> 01:58:22.140
[Amit Varma]: the First Amendment is happening, you write quote, the Prime Minister was essentially

01:58:22.140 --> 01:58:23.740
[Amit Varma]: making three claims.

01:58:23.740 --> 01:58:27.780
[Amit Varma]: First at the failure of the Congress social agenda when confronted with the constitution

01:58:27.780 --> 01:58:30.580
[Amit Varma]: should be regarded as an intolerable situation.

01:58:30.580 --> 01:58:35.020
[Amit Varma]: Since he did not want to face the populace and be accused of breaching his promise, the

01:58:35.020 --> 01:58:38.780
[Amit Varma]: constitution would have to give way to the primacy of the Congress program.

01:58:38.780 --> 01:58:44.140
[Amit Varma]: Second that the social policy is devised by elected legislatures, sites of popular sovereignty,

01:58:44.140 --> 01:58:49.420
[Amit Varma]: being held unconstitutional by the courts was a denial of democracy, even if the legislatures

01:58:49.420 --> 01:58:52.900
[Amit Varma]: had been elected on a distinctly limited and narrow franchise.

01:58:52.900 --> 01:58:56.740
[Amit Varma]: In true democratic spirit, the constitution would have to bend to accommodate the will

01:58:56.740 --> 01:59:02.900
[Amit Varma]: of the people as represented by a legislature elected indirectly, and on a limited franchise.

01:59:02.900 --> 01:59:06.540
[Amit Varma]: Third, the three pillars of the state, the judiciary, the executive and the legislature

01:59:06.540 --> 01:59:07.820
[Amit Varma]: were not equal.

01:59:07.820 --> 01:59:11.000
[Amit Varma]: The executive was to create and give effect to social policy.

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:15.660
[Amit Varma]: And it was to have primacy over the other wings of the state, especially the judiciary.

01:59:15.660 --> 01:59:17.680
[Amit Varma]: It was a slippery slope, stop quote.

01:59:17.680 --> 01:59:21.540
[Amit Varma]: And separately in an interview, you've spoken about how the first amendment showed the judiciary

01:59:21.540 --> 01:59:23.300
[Unknown]: its place.

01:59:23.300 --> 01:59:25.020
[Amit Varma]: So what is the process like now?

01:59:25.020 --> 01:59:30.340
[Amit Varma]: So you know, he wants to, you know, his own cabinet members like Ambedkar Rajaji and whoever

01:59:30.340 --> 01:59:35.900
[Amit Varma]: are on board with him, and Patel, you know, dies in December 1950.

01:59:35.900 --> 01:59:41.060
[Amit Varma]: And the first amendment actually goes for, you know, all the voting happens in May 51.

01:59:41.060 --> 01:59:42.100
[Unknown]: So what's happening?

01:59:42.100 --> 01:59:46.340
[Amit Varma]: You've spoken about all the opposition leaders kind of gathered around in but what's the

01:59:46.340 --> 01:59:50.020
[Amit Varma]: overall sort of what's happening in the political space?

01:59:50.020 --> 01:59:52.580
[Amit Varma]: Like if Republic TV existed, what would they be showing?

01:59:52.580 --> 01:59:56.380
[Amit Varma]: They would still be showing film stars taking drugs, actually.

01:59:56.380 --> 01:59:58.020
[Amit Varma]: So cancel that question.

01:59:58.020 --> 01:59:59.020
[Guest]: But yeah,

01:59:59.020 --> 02:00:04.860
[Guest]: interesting that you you mentioned what the media would be showing, because if you were

02:00:04.860 --> 02:00:10.980
[Guest]: to simply go by Nehru's utterances, the media didn't seem to be all that different back

02:00:10.980 --> 02:00:15.580
[Guest]: in the day, even though we we know it was, but Nehru consistently rails against the media.

02:00:15.580 --> 02:00:20.940
[Guest]: And one of the things he keeps saying, you know, is what will be the effect on our soldiers

02:00:20.940 --> 02:00:25.780
[Guest]: and what will be the effect on our youth of reading this trash?

02:00:25.780 --> 02:00:31.740
[Guest]: So I think he might have probably written the same thing, same thing about Republic.

02:00:31.740 --> 02:00:38.820
[Guest]: But to go back to your question, Nehru makes this claim, the sort of three claims that

02:00:38.820 --> 02:00:41.660
[Guest]: you mentioned, and he makes them quite, quite strongly.

02:00:41.660 --> 02:00:47.060
[Guest]: So there is there is a letter where he basically says that the job of the government is no

02:00:47.060 --> 02:00:53.940
[Guest]: longer simply to, you know, to make policy, it is now to basically direct social change

02:00:53.940 --> 02:00:56.980
[Guest]: and to see it through.

02:00:56.980 --> 02:00:59.700
[Guest]: And he's firmly committed to that line.

02:00:59.700 --> 02:01:06.460
[Guest]: Politically, things kind of progressively reach, at least what he thinks, as a kind

02:01:06.460 --> 02:01:11.660
[Guest]: of difficult time because he's, Zamindari abolition is something that he's very committed

02:01:11.660 --> 02:01:12.660
[Guest]: to.

02:01:12.660 --> 02:01:18.700
[Guest]: Post Patel's death, there is no real challenger within the Congress establishment.

02:01:18.700 --> 02:01:25.980
[Guest]: And as the sort of new year kind of opens, there's this feeling that there has to be

02:01:25.980 --> 02:01:28.780
[Guest]: a sort of reckoning with these questions.

02:01:28.780 --> 02:01:33.900
[Guest]: So what happens is, and again, this is to Nehru's credit, is that Nehru initially aims

02:01:33.900 --> 02:01:38.460
[Guest]: to hold elections in the summer of 1951.

02:01:38.460 --> 02:01:43.340
[Guest]: He's kind of stopped because of obstructionism by the states.

02:01:43.340 --> 02:01:51.700
[Guest]: Many of the states, mainly for these reasons, are kind of not quite ready to test their

02:01:51.700 --> 02:01:52.860
[Guest]: popularity.

02:01:52.860 --> 02:01:57.540
[Guest]: And you can kind of see why, because, for example, in Madras, the Congress fails to

02:01:57.540 --> 02:02:00.300
[Guest]: win a majority in the first election.

02:02:00.300 --> 02:02:05.180
[Guest]: So there's a kind of obstructionism that happens in the states.

02:02:05.180 --> 02:02:08.940
[Guest]: Nehru presses his chief ministers quite hard without success.

02:02:08.940 --> 02:02:13.180
[Guest]: And so elections are eventually delayed.

02:02:13.180 --> 02:02:19.780
[Guest]: And of course, that kind of gives them enough time to basically address these issues before

02:02:19.780 --> 02:02:21.700
[Guest]: going in for election.

02:02:21.700 --> 02:02:27.380
[Guest]: So basically, if I could, on the morning of 25 January 1951, the Congress Working Committee

02:02:27.380 --> 02:02:32.380
[Guest]: meets at Congress headquarters.

02:02:32.380 --> 02:02:36.420
[Guest]: And again, the question, as reported by the press, is they discuss the question of how

02:02:36.420 --> 02:02:39.900
[Guest]: to galvanize the Indian National Congress so as to maintain its moral and political

02:02:39.900 --> 02:02:42.900
[Guest]: hold over the people.

02:02:42.900 --> 02:02:53.140
[Guest]: Over the final quarter of, over the sort of tail end of 1950, Sardar Patel had died.

02:02:53.140 --> 02:02:57.380
[Guest]: There had been the formation of a kind of dissident unit within the Congress called

02:02:57.380 --> 02:03:01.780
[Guest]: the Democratic Front, led by Kriplani and Rafi Ahmad Gidwai.

02:03:01.780 --> 02:03:07.060
[Guest]: There was kind of speculation that several senior figures could quit.

02:03:07.060 --> 02:03:11.420
[Guest]: The Nehru government itself had been, had, you know, three major ministerial resignations

02:03:11.420 --> 02:03:16.080
[Guest]: over 1950, Mathai, Mukherjee, Niyogi.

02:03:16.080 --> 02:03:19.860
[Guest]: And it's sort of surreal to look back now and read the kind of press reports, because

02:03:19.860 --> 02:03:23.660
[Guest]: there are several editorials which keep questioning, being like, will the Congress survive in its

02:03:23.660 --> 02:03:24.660
[Guest]: present form?

02:03:24.660 --> 02:03:26.940
[Guest]: You know, what will be the future?

02:03:26.940 --> 02:03:32.940
[Guest]: And so I think even if it seems surreal to us now to look back and think, well, you know,

02:03:32.940 --> 02:03:38.420
[Guest]: why would people doubt the ability of the Congress to survive in 1951, there were several

02:03:38.420 --> 02:03:39.540
[Guest]: who did.

02:03:39.540 --> 02:03:48.700
[Guest]: And so I think this kind of backdrop is important to remember, and I think that kind of gives

02:03:48.700 --> 02:03:53.740
[Guest]: impetus to this kind of feeling that all these questions now have to be tackled head on before

02:03:53.740 --> 02:03:56.020
[Guest]: they go back to the people.

02:03:56.020 --> 02:04:03.740
[Guest]: And of course, the Allahabad High Court then stops the UP.

02:04:03.740 --> 02:04:11.220
[Guest]: It grants injunctions against the UP Zamindari Abolition Act, which it takes up for examination.

02:04:11.220 --> 02:04:16.900
[Guest]: And that kind of builds this idea that there's almost, the government is sort of under a

02:04:16.900 --> 02:04:22.420
[Guest]: form of judicial siege, because these are, I mean, these are quite big sort of cornerstones

02:04:22.420 --> 02:04:24.740
[Guest]: of government policy.

02:04:24.740 --> 02:04:32.620
[Guest]: So as things build up over the first few months of 1951, you have, in January, you have the

02:04:32.620 --> 02:04:38.220
[Guest]: Allahabad High Court judgment, which effectively stays the operation of the UP Act.

02:04:38.220 --> 02:04:47.340
[Guest]: You then have, in March, the judgment of the Patna High Court, which declares the Bihar

02:04:47.340 --> 02:04:49.340
[Guest]: Act to be unconstitutional.

02:04:49.340 --> 02:04:58.220
[Guest]: And then you also have sort of, in between, you have all of these things kind of brewing

02:04:58.220 --> 02:04:59.220
[Guest]: in the background.

02:04:59.220 --> 02:05:03.580
[Guest]: You have once, you know, Master Tara Singh has been released, as I pointed out in the

02:05:03.580 --> 02:05:11.820
[Guest]: previous part of the conversation, he kind of declares his intention to bring on board,

02:05:11.820 --> 02:05:17.620
[Guest]: invites the communists and the Hindu Mahasabha to join him on a common platform.

02:05:17.620 --> 02:05:24.140
[Guest]: There is this sort of democratic front, which is, you know, bubbling within the Congress.

02:05:24.140 --> 02:05:27.980
[Guest]: So there are all of these, I wouldn't really class it as political turmoil, but there's

02:05:27.980 --> 02:05:33.380
[Guest]: all this, there's a lot of politics going on, going on in the background.

02:05:33.380 --> 02:05:40.260
[Guest]: And I think it kind of leads to a situation where progressively the government, there

02:05:40.260 --> 02:05:46.020
[Guest]: have been adverse judgments in, you know, on huge matters of policy, on reservations,

02:05:46.020 --> 02:05:47.340
[Guest]: on Zamindari abolition.

02:05:47.340 --> 02:05:54.260
[Guest]: And progressively, the impression that one gets from reading Nehru's correspondence is

02:05:54.260 --> 02:05:57.460
[Guest]: a kind of feeling of siege, almost.

02:05:57.460 --> 02:06:05.340
[Guest]: And there is within the Congress broad backing for a kind of collision with the constitution

02:06:05.340 --> 02:06:07.420
[Guest]: and the judiciary.

02:06:07.420 --> 02:06:13.300
[Guest]: And when matters finally reach a head, there is, and you notice that there is more or less

02:06:13.300 --> 02:06:20.340
[Guest]: almost, I wouldn't say universal consensus, but there's more or less like enough support

02:06:20.340 --> 02:06:25.060
[Guest]: within the Congress party for the amendment to be contemplated.

02:06:25.060 --> 02:06:31.220
[Guest]: When it's done, they start drafting it as early as March, even though Nehru publicly

02:06:31.220 --> 02:06:36.220
[Guest]: keeps denying that an amendment is coming or, you know, assures, for example, he attends

02:06:36.220 --> 02:06:40.500
[Guest]: a meeting of the All India Newspaper Editors Conference, where he assures them that the

02:06:40.500 --> 02:06:43.700
[Guest]: freedom of the press is something that is very dear to him.

02:06:43.700 --> 02:06:48.180
[Guest]: And they take it to mean that he has dropped the idea of a constitutional amendment.

02:06:48.180 --> 02:06:53.380
[Guest]: And, you know, they thank him voluminously for his generosity.

02:06:53.380 --> 02:06:56.740
[Guest]: So there's a lot that's going on.

02:06:56.740 --> 02:07:04.300
[Guest]: And politically, the kind of sense that I get is of a government consistently being

02:07:04.300 --> 02:07:12.260
[Guest]: forced onto the back foot and on matters that it considered very close to, if there was

02:07:12.260 --> 02:07:16.660
[Guest]: anything that was a kind of matter of faith within the Congress, those two things definitely

02:07:16.660 --> 02:07:17.660
[Guest]: were it.

02:07:17.660 --> 02:07:18.660
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:07:18.660 --> 02:07:22.180
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, you were speaking with the press and the newspaper editors and it

02:07:22.180 --> 02:07:26.140
[Amit Varma]: kind of made me smile because I'll read out a quote first by the Times of India and then

02:07:26.140 --> 02:07:31.380
[Amit Varma]: Nehru's response, where he sounds less like Nehru and more like Donald Trump, actually.

02:07:31.380 --> 02:07:35.820
[Amit Varma]: But the Times of India quote is, quote, and this is after they come to know of the First

02:07:35.820 --> 02:07:40.380
[Amit Varma]: Amendment, obviously, quote, it is a tragic irony that our popular government should at

02:07:40.380 --> 02:07:45.700
[Amit Varma]: every stage feel the need of repressive laws against which leaders of our struggle for

02:07:45.700 --> 02:07:48.700
[Amit Varma]: freedom cried themselves hoarse for generations.

02:07:48.700 --> 02:07:54.140
[Amit Varma]: The whirling of times brings some strange revenges, the decriers of a government once

02:07:54.140 --> 02:07:59.660
[Amit Varma]: termed satanic, flatter our previous rulers by imitation, they resort to preventive detention

02:07:59.660 --> 02:08:02.500
[Amit Varma]: even without declaring a state of emergency.

02:08:02.500 --> 02:08:03.500
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

02:08:03.500 --> 02:08:06.420
[Amit Varma]: And this is written in 1951, friends, not 2020.

02:08:06.420 --> 02:08:10.340
[Amit Varma]: And Nehru's response to this is, you know, so he speaks to the parliament about the press.

02:08:10.340 --> 02:08:15.820
[Amit Varma]: And then, as you quote him, he's writing to his chief ministers about what he told parliament.

02:08:15.820 --> 02:08:20.820
[Amit Varma]: So he says about that, quote, while appreciating the role of newspapers, generally, I pointed

02:08:20.820 --> 02:08:26.500
[Amit Varma]: out that some weekly periodicals, especially at past all limits of decency, and we're carrying

02:08:26.500 --> 02:08:32.260
[Amit Varma]: on persistently a propaganda full of falsehood and malice to remain silent may also have

02:08:32.260 --> 02:08:33.260
[Amit Varma]: consequences.

02:08:33.260 --> 02:08:36.180
[Amit Varma]: I have appealed to the newspaper editors to take it in hand.

02:08:36.180 --> 02:08:39.500
[Amit Varma]: But if they fail, then something else will have to be thought of.

02:08:39.500 --> 02:08:42.620
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, which is quite a threat at the end of it, that something else will have to

02:08:42.620 --> 02:08:48.460
[Amit Varma]: be thought of and otherwise is fulmination against sort of fake news to use modern terminology

02:08:48.460 --> 02:08:52.700
[Amit Varma]: is reminiscent of leaders one won't often associate with him.

02:08:52.700 --> 02:08:55.380
[Guest]: No, he does it quite often.

02:08:55.380 --> 02:08:59.660
[Guest]: I mean, it's something that is really, really sort of eating into him.

02:08:59.660 --> 02:09:02.660
[Guest]: Because he says it several times in parliament.

02:09:02.660 --> 02:09:09.460
[Guest]: He says it to the when he addresses the all Indian newspapers editors conference.

02:09:09.460 --> 02:09:16.940
[Guest]: And most interestingly, he says it to at the end, when he, you know, after the amendment

02:09:16.940 --> 02:09:21.660
[Guest]: has been passed on 11 June, Nehru was questioned on how the amendment was going to affect the

02:09:21.660 --> 02:09:23.020
[Guest]: press.

02:09:23.020 --> 02:09:27.060
[Guest]: And he says, I do not think that in spite of the heat rays in the recent debates, it

02:09:27.060 --> 02:09:29.020
[Guest]: affects the press much.

02:09:29.020 --> 02:09:32.380
[Guest]: You will forgive me if I say we talk so much of the freedom of the press, but the more

02:09:32.380 --> 02:09:36.840
[Guest]: and more I see that that freedom might as well be exercised by anyone who has money

02:09:36.840 --> 02:09:39.380
[Guest]: enough to buy up a paper.

02:09:39.380 --> 02:09:43.420
[Guest]: Actually it is rather an odd experience for me to see a newspaper within a week or 10

02:09:43.420 --> 02:09:48.940
[Guest]: days completely change its policy tone, and everything except in regard to one matter.

02:09:48.940 --> 02:09:53.060
[Guest]: And that was it's rather extreme dislike of the government and me, that is the freedom

02:09:53.060 --> 02:09:54.060
[Guest]: of the press.

02:09:54.060 --> 02:09:59.380
[Guest]: So, I mean, he's quite, it's quite easy to see that this was something that he took very,

02:09:59.380 --> 02:10:06.180
[Guest]: very seriously, and that he was very averse to any form of criticism.

02:10:06.180 --> 02:10:12.020
[Amit Varma]: No, and it also seems to me that, you know, he would be someone who would have felt entitled

02:10:12.020 --> 02:10:16.140
[Amit Varma]: to the adulation and adoration of his fellow Indians after all these years in the freedom

02:10:16.140 --> 02:10:17.140
[Amit Varma]: struggle.

02:10:17.140 --> 02:10:21.540
[Amit Varma]: But suddenly he's actually replaced, he's in charge of the colonial apparatus, which

02:10:21.540 --> 02:10:23.140
[Amit Varma]: was otherwise oppressing them.

02:10:23.140 --> 02:10:28.540
[Amit Varma]: And I can imagine the sense of entitlement he feels and indeed that his descendants still

02:10:28.540 --> 02:10:31.420
[Amit Varma]: feel that they're not in a similar position of power.

02:10:31.420 --> 02:10:36.220
[Amit Varma]: Another strand that I found interesting in your book was about how, you know, Rajendra

02:10:36.220 --> 02:10:40.460
[Amit Varma]: Prasad, the president at the time, spoke out against him and, you know, repeatedly asked

02:10:40.460 --> 02:10:42.700
[Amit Varma]: him not to go ahead with the first amendment.

02:10:42.700 --> 02:10:46.820
[Amit Varma]: At one point, Rajendra Prasad says, quote, part three of the constitution which lays

02:10:46.820 --> 02:10:51.340
[Amit Varma]: down the fundamental rights has a special importance and significance of its own.

02:10:51.340 --> 02:10:56.500
[Amit Varma]: And it's an irony of late that this part which stands above every other part of the constitution

02:10:56.500 --> 02:10:59.100
[Amit Varma]: is the first to be assailed, stop quote.

02:10:59.100 --> 02:11:04.860
[Amit Varma]: And you also point out, and this seemed very strange and petty to me, that when, you know,

02:11:04.860 --> 02:11:08.900
[Amit Varma]: he wrote this letter to the cabinet and Nehru said he'll read it out to the cabinet.

02:11:08.900 --> 02:11:13.900
[Amit Varma]: But then he writes to him, quote, it would be exceedingly unfortunate if the public became

02:11:13.900 --> 02:11:18.300
[Amit Varma]: aware that the president had a contrary position to that of the cabinet in such a matter and

02:11:18.300 --> 02:11:24.100
[Amit Varma]: was pressing for his adoption by the cabinet, stop quote, in effect telling, you know, Prasad

02:11:24.100 --> 02:11:25.660
[Amit Varma]: to shut up.

02:11:25.660 --> 02:11:28.980
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how was this sort of dynamic playing out?

02:11:28.980 --> 02:11:33.420
[Amit Varma]: I mean, today, of course, the president is a figurehead, but Rajendra Prasad was a heavyweight

02:11:33.420 --> 02:11:38.780
[Amit Varma]: leader in the Congress party and, you know, and how was all of this playing out?

02:11:38.780 --> 02:11:43.580
[Guest]: It's very interesting because Prasad and Nehru dynamic went through its ups and downs.

02:11:43.580 --> 02:11:47.660
[Guest]: Prasad, for starters, considered himself Nehru's equal.

02:11:47.660 --> 02:11:55.300
[Guest]: Secondly, his own conception of the president's role was not simply, I mean, he took the idea

02:11:55.300 --> 02:11:59.140
[Guest]: that he was to advise and guide quite seriously.

02:11:59.140 --> 02:12:03.740
[Guest]: So he wasn't a rubber stamp sort of president.

02:12:03.740 --> 02:12:10.220
[Guest]: And equally, Prasad was very willing to intervene in government and let his views be known.

02:12:10.220 --> 02:12:16.380
[Guest]: But crucially, he was well aware of the sort of need to maintain constitutional rectitude

02:12:16.380 --> 02:12:18.820
[Guest]: or, you know, set good precedents.

02:12:18.820 --> 02:12:21.700
[Guest]: And so, for example, when Nehru writes to him and tells him it would be exceedingly

02:12:21.700 --> 02:12:28.820
[Guest]: unfortunate if your views were to become publicly known, Prasad actually doesn't let his views

02:12:28.820 --> 02:12:29.820
[Guest]: be publicly known.

02:12:29.820 --> 02:12:34.980
[Guest]: I mean, he's willing to write to the prime minister, but he's not willing to kind of

02:12:34.980 --> 02:12:40.620
[Guest]: jeopardize the whole setup by stepping outside constitutional bounds, which, to be honest,

02:12:40.620 --> 02:12:45.900
[Guest]: he could have done if he really wanted to, but he doesn't.

02:12:45.900 --> 02:12:52.460
[Guest]: And the same thing kind of happens when the Zamindari Abolition Act is passed.

02:12:52.460 --> 02:12:57.420
[Guest]: The president has to certify the Zamindari Abolition Act because it obviously contravenes

02:12:57.420 --> 02:13:02.340
[Guest]: a part of the constitution, and it can be saved, or at least it's assumed to be saved

02:13:02.340 --> 02:13:07.980
[Guest]: by a presidential notification or presidential approval.

02:13:07.980 --> 02:13:14.740
[Guest]: And when he gets the Bihar law, Rajendra Prasad obviously recognizes the flaws in it.

02:13:14.740 --> 02:13:18.900
[Guest]: And he kind of tarries by asking for legal opinion, and he sits on it.

02:13:18.900 --> 02:13:24.020
[Guest]: And you know, Nehru writes to him again, when I quote, and he says, and effectively tells

02:13:24.020 --> 02:13:28.900
[Guest]: him that the cabinet have agreed to it, and threatens to resign if the president doesn't

02:13:28.900 --> 02:13:30.500
[Guest]: certify the act.

02:13:30.500 --> 02:13:34.920
[Guest]: And of course, Prasad then promptly does certify it, even though he doesn't really quite agree

02:13:34.920 --> 02:13:40.020
[Guest]: with Nehru or recognize what the need for this sort of daring hurry is.

02:13:40.020 --> 02:13:45.500
[Guest]: So it's interesting to note that Prasad takes his role seriously, but is also effectively

02:13:45.500 --> 02:13:47.380
[Guest]: very committed to the constitutional order.

02:13:47.380 --> 02:13:52.500
[Guest]: At no point does he seek to kind of overturn it or to even intervene in a way that could

02:13:52.500 --> 02:13:58.000
[Guest]: be seen to be deliberately intervening in areas of government that he really should

02:13:58.000 --> 02:14:00.640
[Guest]: not be intervening in.

02:14:00.640 --> 02:14:04.060
[Guest]: So that is a very, very interesting dynamic.

02:14:04.060 --> 02:14:12.140
[Guest]: Especially when Nehru often thinks that Rajendra Prasad has a propensity to exceed his brief,

02:14:12.140 --> 02:14:18.500
[Guest]: because his reading of the situation is that the president is duty bound to follow the

02:14:18.500 --> 02:14:21.100
[Guest]: advice of his council of ministers.

02:14:21.100 --> 02:14:25.900
[Guest]: And things kind of come to a head when the amendment reaches Rajendra Prasad, because

02:14:25.900 --> 02:14:28.100
[Guest]: he obviously doesn't sign it immediately.

02:14:28.100 --> 02:14:34.020
[Guest]: He seeks legal opinion, because he thinks the amendment itself might well be unconstitutional,

02:14:34.020 --> 02:14:41.620
[Guest]: because the method used to pass it, coincidentally, eerily similar to what was used recently in

02:14:41.620 --> 02:14:43.540
[Guest]: the case of Article 370.

02:14:43.540 --> 02:14:47.900
[Guest]: So Prasad suspects that the amendment itself may be unconstitutional, and he asks for advice

02:14:47.900 --> 02:14:53.700
[Guest]: from Alladi Krishnaswami Iyer, whose advice we don't have on record.

02:14:53.700 --> 02:14:56.300
[Guest]: But obviously, Prasad signs it in the end.

02:14:56.300 --> 02:15:03.920
[Guest]: So I think the legal advice he received probably indicated that that's what he should do.

02:15:03.920 --> 02:15:08.180
[Guest]: So it's, it's a very interesting dynamic, but Prasad doesn't shy away from letting his

02:15:08.180 --> 02:15:09.180
[Guest]: views be known.

02:15:09.180 --> 02:15:13.900
[Guest]: And in most cases, those views are quite the opposite of what the government has.

02:15:13.900 --> 02:15:18.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's quite remarkable, because if in the current day, you know, your president

02:15:18.820 --> 02:15:23.700
[Amit Varma]: receives a letter like that, it's like leaked in 30 seconds, and on times now and all of

02:15:23.700 --> 02:15:24.700
[Amit Varma]: that.

02:15:24.700 --> 02:15:29.580
[Amit Varma]: So and your book also has this unlikely sort of liberal hero now you'd expect, you know,

02:15:29.580 --> 02:15:33.380
[Amit Varma]: for many people seem to think of Nehru as a liberal hero for some reason, but Nehru is

02:15:33.380 --> 02:15:37.780
[Amit Varma]: a person who says, Oh, these fundamental rights are a 19th century artifact, we are not in

02:15:37.780 --> 02:15:41.020
[Amit Varma]: the French Revolution, and, you know, blah, blah, blah.

02:15:41.020 --> 02:15:45.180
[Amit Varma]: But the person who is really defending them and defending them with great eloquence and

02:15:45.180 --> 02:15:50.620
[Amit Varma]: passion is Shama Prasad Mukherjee, where he talks about how the First Amendment cuts court

02:15:50.620 --> 02:15:55.540
[Amit Varma]: at the very root of the fundamental principles of the Constitution, he calls it quote, the

02:15:55.540 --> 02:16:00.060
[Amit Varma]: beginning of the encroachment of the liberty of the people of free India, stop quote, and

02:16:00.060 --> 02:16:05.260
[Amit Varma]: then addressing Nehru during the heated debates, he says, quote, by this amendment, you are

02:16:05.260 --> 02:16:10.220
[Amit Varma]: saying that whatever legislation is passed, it is deemed to be law, then why have your

02:16:10.220 --> 02:16:11.220
[Amit Varma]: Constitution?

02:16:11.220 --> 02:16:12.220
[Amit Varma]: Why have your fundamental rights?

02:16:12.220 --> 02:16:15.860
[Amit Varma]: Who asked you to have fundamental rights at all, you are treating the Constitution as

02:16:15.860 --> 02:16:20.220
[Amit Varma]: a scrap of paper, stop quote, and at one point, Nehru got irritated and apparently wanted

02:16:20.220 --> 02:16:23.700
[Amit Varma]: to charge him with sedition and only Patel stopped him from doing that.

02:16:23.700 --> 02:16:29.020
[Amit Varma]: But you know, what is our sense of Mukherjee because there isn't much written about him

02:16:29.020 --> 02:16:33.940
[Amit Varma]: to my knowledge, there isn't a great biography, he didn't really leave much writing behind.

02:16:33.940 --> 02:16:37.460
[Amit Varma]: But you know, you read him in the constitutional debates with Nehru and so on.

02:16:37.460 --> 02:16:40.820
[Amit Varma]: And this seems like, you know, one of the tallest, most principled leaders.

02:16:40.820 --> 02:16:43.220
[Guest]: So what's your sense of all of that?

02:16:43.220 --> 02:16:46.580
[Guest]: He was he was actually a remarkably principled man.

02:16:46.580 --> 02:16:51.700
[Guest]: And he that's borne out by, for example, his resignation from the Nehru cabinet.

02:16:51.700 --> 02:16:56.900
[Guest]: It's also borne out, quite importantly, by his resignation from the Hindu Mahasabha,

02:16:56.900 --> 02:17:02.380
[Guest]: because what people don't realize is that he quit the Hindu Mahasabha, because he felt

02:17:02.380 --> 02:17:09.500
[Guest]: that once we have a secular state, there was no need or no space for a quote unquote, Hindu

02:17:09.500 --> 02:17:11.180
[Guest]: party anymore.

02:17:11.180 --> 02:17:17.260
[Guest]: So he's that way, he's a very, very interesting and complex figure to look at.

02:17:17.260 --> 02:17:21.380
[Guest]: But and one of the things that comes across in these debates with Nehru is that unlike

02:17:21.380 --> 02:17:29.180
[Guest]: Nehru, whose debates are very impassioned, but also often short on facts and logic, Mukherjee

02:17:29.180 --> 02:17:31.460
[Guest]: is a very incisive speaker.

02:17:31.460 --> 02:17:36.380
[Guest]: And it's again, this is borne out when they speak, because most of the time when the debate

02:17:36.380 --> 02:17:41.420
[Guest]: happens, obviously Nehru presents his case, and then Mukherjee replies as the leader of

02:17:41.420 --> 02:17:43.420
[Guest]: the opposition.

02:17:43.420 --> 02:17:47.740
[Guest]: So the first time the bill is kind of debated in Parliament, Mukherjee replies and immediately

02:17:47.740 --> 02:17:53.660
[Guest]: after Mukherjee replies, the person to speak is NG Ranga, Congress stalwart, later one

02:17:53.660 --> 02:17:58.780
[Guest]: of the founders of the Swatantra Party, and he compares Mukherjee to Edmund Burke, and

02:17:58.780 --> 02:18:03.420
[Guest]: calls it one of the greatest speeches that he's ever heard in Indian Parliament.

02:18:03.420 --> 02:18:09.940
[Guest]: So it's interesting to note, the kind of impression that you get of Mukherjee is very unlike what

02:18:09.940 --> 02:18:14.420
[Guest]: is often believed, because you hear of him in the context of Kashmir, in the context

02:18:14.420 --> 02:18:22.820
[Guest]: of 370, but you often don't hear of him in the context of freedom of speech, for example.

02:18:22.820 --> 02:18:27.140
[Guest]: And Mukherjee is one of the most dogged defenders of that freedom, and in many ways very, very

02:18:27.140 --> 02:18:34.820
[Guest]: patient, because he keeps, one of the reasons that he criticises Nehru again, is because

02:18:34.820 --> 02:18:40.860
[Guest]: he's well aware that what Nehru is doing is laying a precedent for something far worse

02:18:40.860 --> 02:18:47.780
[Guest]: in the future, or in some ways providing legal and constitutional tools that are prone to

02:18:47.780 --> 02:18:58.980
[Guest]: misuse by anyone who is willing to transcend his scruples, or his commitment to constitutionalism.

02:18:58.980 --> 02:19:09.260
[Guest]: And Mukherjee almost leads the kind of charge against the bill, and I think he makes a very,

02:19:09.260 --> 02:19:14.180
[Guest]: very successful case for himself, and for the opposition.

02:19:14.180 --> 02:19:19.780
[Guest]: It's reported widely in the press, it's, again, commentators often note that, you know, whatever

02:19:19.780 --> 02:19:27.380
[Guest]: of the, I think the line that I remember offhand is the Times of India describing the debate

02:19:27.380 --> 02:19:32.780
[Guest]: between Nehru and Mukherjee and noting that the Prime Minister's passion was more than

02:19:32.780 --> 02:19:40.020
[Guest]: outmatched by the incisive logic of Mukherjee's arguments, and I think that it's, that's quite

02:19:40.020 --> 02:19:47.380
[Guest]: apparent that he sort of read between the lines of what was happening far more clearly

02:19:47.380 --> 02:19:53.620
[Guest]: than many of the others did, and he was willing to stake out a principled position, despite

02:19:53.620 --> 02:20:00.820
[Guest]: the fact that it had, you know, caused him to leave the Nehru cabinet, almost kind of

02:20:00.820 --> 02:20:07.180
[Guest]: enter the political wilderness, and in many ways, take out a position that many of his

02:20:07.180 --> 02:20:12.540
[Guest]: own ideological fellow travelers are perhaps not the most comfortable with.

02:20:12.540 --> 02:20:16.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it would seem that, you know, Mukherjee was, of course, borne out by history, not

02:20:16.380 --> 02:20:20.180
[Amit Varma]: the history of the last few decades, but just the history of the next few years, in the

02:20:20.180 --> 02:20:26.100
[Amit Varma]: sense that it wasn't just about those specific amendments or those specific policies, which

02:20:26.100 --> 02:20:31.460
[Amit Varma]: Nehru wanted to get through, but about the desecration of the constitution and of constitutionalism

02:20:31.460 --> 02:20:36.700
[Amit Varma]: itself, you know, which had led Justice, Chief Justice Hidayatullah to once quip that ours

02:20:36.700 --> 02:20:41.140
[Amit Varma]: was the only constitution which needed protection against itself.

02:20:41.140 --> 02:20:45.220
[Amit Varma]: And the father of our constitution, B. R. Ambedkar, in fact, in 1954, I think after

02:20:45.220 --> 02:20:49.620
[Amit Varma]: the Fourth Amendment, when he was no longer in government, said, quote, we built a temple

02:20:49.620 --> 02:20:53.860
[Amit Varma]: for a god to come in and recite, but before the god could be installed, if the devil has

02:20:53.860 --> 02:20:57.740
[Amit Varma]: taken possession of it, what else could we do except destroy the temple?

02:20:57.740 --> 02:21:02.180
[Amit Varma]: We did not intend that it should be occupied by the Asuras, we intended it to be occupied

02:21:02.180 --> 02:21:03.420
[Amit Varma]: by the Devas.

02:21:03.420 --> 02:21:08.260
[Amit Varma]: That is the reason I said, I would rather like to burn it, stop quote, which are strong

02:21:08.260 --> 02:21:15.460
[Amit Varma]: words from someone who actually, you know, was a driving force behind our constitution.

02:21:15.460 --> 02:21:19.820
[Amit Varma]: Let's so you know, eventually it gets passed and it's a done deal.

02:21:19.820 --> 02:21:24.300
[Amit Varma]: You've, you know, sort of, I want to ask you about the aftermath, but before that, I'll

02:21:24.300 --> 02:21:30.460
[Amit Varma]: quickly quote you from your book where you've written this very eloquent passage, quote,

02:21:30.460 --> 02:21:34.380
[Amit Varma]: the relationship between the state and the citizen was altered for all time.

02:21:34.380 --> 02:21:39.420
[Amit Varma]: The precedent was set for easy, almost casual amending of the constitution and the passing

02:21:39.420 --> 02:21:45.100
[Amit Varma]: of retrospective legislation, a mechanism for bypassing judicial review was created.

02:21:45.100 --> 02:21:49.300
[Amit Varma]: Sedition had been retrospectively validated, a host of public safety and press control

02:21:49.300 --> 02:21:52.300
[Amit Varma]: laws had been made operational again.

02:21:52.300 --> 02:21:56.220
[Amit Varma]: Free speech was curtailed, no longer would it be necessary for the security of the state

02:21:56.220 --> 02:21:59.940
[Amit Varma]: to be seriously undermined for it to prescribe free expression.

02:21:59.940 --> 02:22:02.460
[Amit Varma]: It merely had to be in his interest to do so.

02:22:02.460 --> 02:22:06.140
[Amit Varma]: The subservience of the constitution to government policy was demonstrated.

02:22:06.140 --> 02:22:10.140
[Amit Varma]: The constitutional groundwork was laid for a host of repressive legislation to follow.

02:22:10.140 --> 02:22:14.540
[Amit Varma]: A vital cardinal change had occurred, which would have immense long-term consequences

02:22:14.540 --> 02:22:18.540
[Amit Varma]: for India, its people, and its politics, stop quote.

02:22:18.540 --> 02:22:22.940
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, you know, despite people paying so much lip service, I mean, people

02:22:22.940 --> 02:22:27.060
[Amit Varma]: pay so much lip service to the constitution, even, you know, prime minister Modi once said

02:22:27.060 --> 02:22:33.460
[Amit Varma]: that it's his holy book and, and you know, for all practical purposes, the constitution

02:22:33.460 --> 02:22:38.860
[Amit Varma]: is like what Mukherjee said, Nehru was turning it into a scrap of paper where any government,

02:22:38.860 --> 02:22:43.980
[Amit Varma]: if it has the numbers can just change it and it's nowhere near as liberal as many people

02:22:43.980 --> 02:22:45.300
[Amit Varma]: seem to think it is.

02:22:45.300 --> 02:22:49.540
[Amit Varma]: And this is becoming, you know, more and more explicit by the day if it wasn't already before.

02:22:49.540 --> 02:22:52.060
[Amit Varma]: What do you think are sort of the consequences for this?

02:22:52.060 --> 02:22:56.380
[Amit Varma]: Does the constitution no longer matter or, you know, different question entirely perhaps,

02:22:56.380 --> 02:22:59.020
[Amit Varma]: do those principles no longer matter?

02:22:59.020 --> 02:23:01.900
[Amit Varma]: Was the experiment doomed to failure from the start?

02:23:01.900 --> 02:23:05.740
[Guest]: I'm not sure whether I would say the experiment was doomed to failure from the start.

02:23:05.740 --> 02:23:11.020
[Guest]: I think it was, it was quite a brave leap of faith and everyone involved acknowledged

02:23:11.020 --> 02:23:13.980
[Guest]: it as, as a leap of faith.

02:23:13.980 --> 02:23:17.220
[Guest]: But I think, again, I'll quote you.

02:23:17.220 --> 02:23:22.820
[Guest]: It's a quote that I took from Sunil Killani again, where he says, basically, in a setting

02:23:22.820 --> 02:23:27.780
[Guest]: such as India, individuality as a way of social being was a precarious undertaking.

02:23:27.780 --> 02:23:33.260
[Guest]: And then he describes Indian liberalism to be crippled from its origins, stamped by utilitarianism

02:23:33.260 --> 02:23:37.260
[Guest]: and squeezed into a culture that had little room for the individual.

02:23:37.260 --> 02:23:42.340
[Guest]: So we, I mean, everyone knew that it was a kind of challenging project to begin with.

02:23:42.340 --> 02:23:47.780
[Guest]: It was never going to be easy, it was never going to be, how should I put it, clean in

02:23:47.780 --> 02:23:48.780
[Guest]: a way.

02:23:48.780 --> 02:23:50.620
[Guest]: It was always going to be a messy process.

02:23:50.620 --> 02:23:54.500
[Guest]: But I wouldn't say it was kind of doomed to failure.

02:23:54.500 --> 02:23:59.740
[Guest]: If anything, the kind of first, the story of the First Amendment proves that actually

02:23:59.740 --> 02:24:05.660
[Guest]: there were many who were willing to, you know, take it at face value to judiciary certainly

02:24:05.660 --> 02:24:06.660
[Guest]: was.

02:24:06.660 --> 02:24:15.860
[Guest]: They were willing to uphold constitutional freedoms and kind of read them quite expansively.

02:24:15.860 --> 02:24:21.260
[Guest]: There was certainly quite important figures within the political setup who seemed to be

02:24:21.260 --> 02:24:26.100
[Guest]: at least to be votaries of constitutional freedoms.

02:24:26.100 --> 02:24:33.020
[Guest]: There was a press that was quite vigorous in its sort of position and defense of the

02:24:33.020 --> 02:24:35.460
[Guest]: right to free speech.

02:24:35.460 --> 02:24:39.220
[Guest]: Governments such as the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry, who I mean

02:24:39.220 --> 02:24:44.900
[Guest]: today we would term as probably completely obsequious, was, for example, willing to stand

02:24:44.900 --> 02:24:52.580
[Guest]: up and, you know, and be counted in a matter of, you know, such political importance.

02:24:52.580 --> 02:24:56.140
[Guest]: So I don't think I would say it was doomed to failure.

02:24:56.140 --> 02:25:01.540
[Guest]: I mean, if anything, that kind of year proved that there was, that it could actually have

02:25:01.540 --> 02:25:09.340
[Guest]: been quite a successful experiment if it hadn't really been betrayed in its sort of essentials

02:25:09.340 --> 02:25:13.820
[Guest]: by the people who kind of midwife the experiment to begin with.

02:25:13.820 --> 02:25:18.100
[Guest]: I mean, we can't deny that these are the people who also wrote up the Constitution.

02:25:18.100 --> 02:25:24.260
[Guest]: So it was, I mean, it was their experiment and they failed it more than anything else.

02:25:24.260 --> 02:25:29.140
[Amit Varma]: And do you think sort of institutions also shape society in a deeper way?

02:25:29.140 --> 02:25:32.620
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, there's this common lament that, oh, look, you know, at the time

02:25:32.620 --> 02:25:37.020
[Amit Varma]: of our independence, at the time of our freedom struggle, we had such tall leaders and we

02:25:37.020 --> 02:25:43.180
[Amit Varma]: have such not tall leaders now, so to say, and I've written a column again using incentives

02:25:43.180 --> 02:25:46.740
[Amit Varma]: to sort of talk about this while pointing out that all the freedom fighters who came

02:25:46.740 --> 02:25:51.780
[Amit Varma]: to the fore and who were tall leaders at the time of our independence had entered the freedom

02:25:51.780 --> 02:25:56.060
[Amit Varma]: struggle and become leaders, not because they had power at the end of it or money at the

02:25:56.060 --> 02:25:57.060
[Amit Varma]: end of it.

02:25:57.060 --> 02:25:58.540
[Amit Varma]: They did it just to stand up for principles.

02:25:58.540 --> 02:25:59.740
[Amit Varma]: There was no reward.

02:25:59.740 --> 02:26:02.620
[Amit Varma]: So politics attracted that kind of a person.

02:26:02.620 --> 02:26:08.660
[Amit Varma]: But when you have, later on, when you have a sort of a structure where there's a state

02:26:08.660 --> 02:26:14.700
[Amit Varma]: is an overarching my barb and has so much power and essentially the similar oppressive

02:26:14.700 --> 02:26:20.860
[Amit Varma]: role to what the colonial state had, then it will draw the kind of leaders who are attracted

02:26:20.860 --> 02:26:24.000
[Amit Varma]: to power for power's sake and power to whatever.

02:26:24.000 --> 02:26:27.780
[Amit Varma]: And therefore those tall principle leaders will no longer emerge.

02:26:27.780 --> 02:26:32.460
[Amit Varma]: And it would seem to me that the degrading of the constitution in a sense would also

02:26:32.460 --> 02:26:39.700
[Amit Varma]: have been a further disincentive for people of principle to actually enter the fray.

02:26:39.700 --> 02:26:40.900
[Guest]: Do you think there's something to that?

02:26:40.900 --> 02:26:44.380
[Guest]: I mean, I think it's yes, yes and no.

02:26:44.380 --> 02:26:50.860
[Guest]: So yes, sort of institutions and, you know, precedence and the law itself and the constitution

02:26:50.860 --> 02:26:54.300
[Guest]: itself do shape society in certain ways.

02:26:54.300 --> 02:27:01.700
[Guest]: I mean, it's hard to deny or even overstate the kind of normative power that they wield.

02:27:01.700 --> 02:27:07.180
[Guest]: Even today, for example, protesters who hold copies of the constitution aloft, kind of

02:27:07.180 --> 02:27:11.100
[Guest]: what they try to do is they're trying to channel the normative power of the constitution rather

02:27:11.100 --> 02:27:16.740
[Guest]: than, you know, actually looking at the nitty gritties of what the constitution says.

02:27:16.740 --> 02:27:21.660
[Guest]: I'm quite shocked if they were to actually see what the constitution says.

02:27:21.660 --> 02:27:29.100
[Guest]: But it's one of the reasons that the constitution was written in the way that it was, was that

02:27:29.100 --> 02:27:35.060
[Guest]: a lot of figures, Ambedkar especially, had little faith in the ability of Indian society

02:27:35.060 --> 02:27:42.340
[Guest]: to reform itself or for there to be a sense of corrective impulse originating from within

02:27:42.340 --> 02:27:44.340
[Guest]: society.

02:27:44.340 --> 02:27:49.540
[Guest]: And because they didn't have that faith in the self-correcting ability of society almost

02:27:49.540 --> 02:27:55.180
[Guest]: or the possibility of any idea of social reform really originating from within society or

02:27:55.180 --> 02:28:03.580
[Guest]: taking hold organically within society, they almost had an over-dependence on using legal

02:28:03.580 --> 02:28:09.900
[Guest]: forms to drive what they saw as social or political change.

02:28:09.900 --> 02:28:15.620
[Guest]: And ultimately, I mean, recently Pratap Bhanu Mehta, for example, wrote a column where he

02:28:15.620 --> 02:28:23.500
[Guest]: very generously quoted from my book, but again, the sort of crux of the column was that there's

02:28:23.500 --> 02:28:30.420
[Guest]: only so much that can be accomplished by the use of legal and constitutional tools, I mean,

02:28:30.420 --> 02:28:38.860
[Guest]: if fundamentally social questions can only partially be addressed in terms of legality.

02:28:38.860 --> 02:28:46.820
[Guest]: And I think that's one point where figures like Nehru and Ambedkar were perhaps over-enthusiastic

02:28:46.820 --> 02:28:51.180
[Guest]: about how much the law could achieve.

02:28:51.180 --> 02:28:56.340
[Guest]: And secondly, I think they were perhaps quite cavalier in thinking about the effects that

02:28:56.340 --> 02:29:04.700
[Guest]: would be generated by these sort of institutional mechanisms, because Nehru, for example, seemed

02:29:04.700 --> 02:29:13.940
[Guest]: almost unaware, I mean, and it's hard to judge whether he was deliberately ignorant or genuinely

02:29:13.940 --> 02:29:20.540
[Guest]: unaware of the kind of incentives that would be generated or the kind of consequences that

02:29:20.540 --> 02:29:22.940
[Guest]: would be generated through the First Amendment.

02:29:22.940 --> 02:29:24.740
[Guest]: It's hard to tell.

02:29:24.740 --> 02:29:33.220
[Guest]: You could, I mean, at best he was naive, at worst he was, you know, malevolent.

02:29:33.220 --> 02:29:38.220
[Guest]: And so I think both these strands kind of intersected at this point.

02:29:38.220 --> 02:29:42.620
[Amit Varma]: So sort of leaving history aside now and leaving your book aside and coming to the present

02:29:42.620 --> 02:29:46.620
[Amit Varma]: moment and coming to the personal, I'm curious about how your book has been received.

02:29:46.620 --> 02:29:50.060
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, as we discussed at the start of the show, we are in times where history

02:29:50.060 --> 02:29:56.940
[Amit Varma]: has been weaponized, where Nehru is looked upon as on one side as exclusively the ideal

02:29:56.940 --> 02:30:01.700
[Amit Varma]: liberal who could do no wrong and on the other side as this demon who is responsible for

02:30:01.700 --> 02:30:03.860
[Amit Varma]: everything that has gone wrong with India.

02:30:03.860 --> 02:30:08.380
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, like any person, and as your book acknowledges, you know, all figures in

02:30:08.380 --> 02:30:09.820
[Amit Varma]: history contain multitude.

02:30:09.820 --> 02:30:12.900
[Amit Varma]: So all of it is true, and all of it is false and all of that.

02:30:12.900 --> 02:30:17.220
[Amit Varma]: But I would imagine that nevertheless, in your book, it would seem as if it's ideal

02:30:17.220 --> 02:30:22.660
[Amit Varma]: fodder for those who want to blame Nehru for where India is today.

02:30:22.660 --> 02:30:24.580
[Amit Varma]: So is that something you were wary of?

02:30:24.580 --> 02:30:29.240
[Amit Varma]: And has that impacted the way your book has been read, where people are not actually reading

02:30:29.240 --> 02:30:33.660
[Amit Varma]: the book for the nuance and the history, but they are just sort of weaponizing it?

02:30:33.660 --> 02:30:34.660
[Guest]: Has that happened?

02:30:34.660 --> 02:30:35.660
[Guest]: I don't think so.

02:30:35.660 --> 02:30:39.140
[Guest]: I mean, I think history is always complex.

02:30:39.140 --> 02:30:46.940
[Guest]: And it's always, I don't think the job of a historian is to be kind, really, to anyone.

02:30:46.940 --> 02:30:52.940
[Guest]: It's to be as kind of as incisive as possible and shine the spotlight as bright as you can.

02:30:52.940 --> 02:30:54.900
[Guest]: And that's something that I've tried to do.

02:30:54.900 --> 02:30:59.940
[Guest]: I think, I'm sure there are people who've read it, because it can provide sort of intellectual

02:30:59.940 --> 02:31:03.580
[Guest]: fodder for an attack on Nehru and Nehruvinism.

02:31:03.580 --> 02:31:08.340
[Guest]: And I'm sure there are some people who've read it or have perhaps used it like that.

02:31:08.340 --> 02:31:11.900
[Guest]: But most reviews have generally been quite complimentary.

02:31:11.900 --> 02:31:17.380
[Guest]: We've most of, yeah, the book doesn't set out to target Nehru.

02:31:17.380 --> 02:31:22.100
[Guest]: It's just that the things unfold in the way they do.

02:31:22.100 --> 02:31:25.900
[Guest]: And the episode is not particularly complimentary to Nehru.

02:31:25.900 --> 02:31:30.020
[Guest]: But equally, I think it's very revealing in the way that it kind of looks at Nehru as

02:31:30.020 --> 02:31:33.260
[Guest]: well, because Nehru had many aspects to his personality.

02:31:33.260 --> 02:31:38.180
[Guest]: And the fact that he was impatient, kind of authoritarian, imperious in many ways.

02:31:38.180 --> 02:31:43.580
[Guest]: I mean, those aspects of his personality are as important as anything else, as his sort

02:31:43.580 --> 02:31:48.740
[Guest]: of commitment, often kind of pedantic and tendentious, as it were, his commitment to

02:31:48.740 --> 02:31:52.820
[Guest]: democracy, to the idea of collective decision making, etc.

02:31:52.820 --> 02:31:58.380
[Guest]: And so to have a more complete or rounded picture, you need both sides.

02:31:58.380 --> 02:32:02.740
[Guest]: And I think in that way, this story is very, very revealing.

02:32:02.740 --> 02:32:06.340
[Guest]: But some perhaps might have used the book in that way.

02:32:06.340 --> 02:32:09.020
[Guest]: But I think most people have taken it in the right spirit.

02:32:09.020 --> 02:32:15.540
[Guest]: I haven't really seen, all of the reviews have been quite sort of complimentary and

02:32:15.540 --> 02:32:21.220
[Guest]: not quite, nobody has really kind of seen the book as a sort of weapon against Nehru.

02:32:21.220 --> 02:32:24.340
[Guest]: I mean, it is what it is.

02:32:24.340 --> 02:32:30.220
[Guest]: Just one more point, if I make it, is that I'm sure there are plenty of people who would

02:32:30.220 --> 02:32:35.220
[Guest]: have disliked it or not read it or not engaged with it, equally, because they see Nehru as

02:32:35.220 --> 02:32:43.660
[Guest]: this kind of, you know, grand liberal figure who I've kind of set out to defame.

02:32:43.660 --> 02:32:45.940
[Guest]: And so neither of those things are true.

02:32:45.940 --> 02:32:50.700
[Guest]: I mean, history is neither kind nor generous, it just is.

02:32:50.700 --> 02:32:51.700
[Amit Varma]: It is what it is.

02:32:51.700 --> 02:32:54.460
[Amit Varma]: And I found your book was, you know, very fair to all the characters.

02:32:54.460 --> 02:32:59.580
[Amit Varma]: And what I found especially revealing about your book is not so much necessarily the people

02:32:59.580 --> 02:33:04.860
[Amit Varma]: and the events involved, but also how it shows through them, that intersection of human nature

02:33:04.860 --> 02:33:09.940
[Amit Varma]: and the structure of our politics, and how, you know, people in positions of power are

02:33:09.940 --> 02:33:14.420
[Amit Varma]: corrupted by that power and are, you know, responding to incentives.

02:33:14.420 --> 02:33:18.180
[Amit Varma]: I had a great time reading your book, and I recommend to all my listeners that they

02:33:18.180 --> 02:33:19.180
[Amit Varma]: go out and buy it.

